% Here is TeX material that gets inserted after \input webmaca
\def\hang{\hangindent 3em\indent\ignorespaces}
\font\ninerm=cmr9
\let\mc=\ninerm % medium caps for names like ADA
\def\ADA{{\mc ADA}}
\def\ab{$\.|\ldots\.|$} % ADA brackets (|...|)
\def\v{\.{\char'174}} % vertical (|) in typewriter font
\mathchardef\BA="3224 % double arrow
\def\({} % kludge for alphabetizing certain module names
 
\def\title{ATANGLE}
\def\contentspagenumber{137} % should be odd
\def\topofcontents{\null\vfill
  \titlefalse % include headline on the contents page
  \def\rheader{\mainfont Appendix E\hfil \contentspagenumber}
  \centerline{\titlefont The {\ttitlefont ATANGLE} processor}
  \vskip 15pt
  \centerline{(based on {\tt TANGLE} Version 2.8)}
  \centerline{{\ninerm[ADA-Version 1.0]}}
  \vfill}
\pageno=\contentspagenumber \advance\pageno by 1
 
@* Introduction.
This program converts an \.{AWEB} file to an \ADA\ file. It was written%
---originally for conversion to {\mc PASCAL}---by D. E. Knuth in September, 
1981; a somewhat similar {\mc SAIL} program had been developed in March, 
1979. Since this program describes itself, a bootstrapping process involving 
hand-translation had to be used to get started. The conversion to \ADA\
has been done by U. Schweigert in May 1988.

For large \.{AWEB} files one should have a large memory, since \.{ATANGLE}
keeps all the \ADA\ text in memory (in an abbreviated form). This program
uses only \ADA-features as described in ``The Programming Language \ADA\
Reference Manual'' and is thus conform with ANSI/MIL-STD-1815A-1983.
 
The system-dependent portions of \.{ATANGLE} can be identified by looking at
the entries for `system dependencies' in the index below.
@!@^system dependencies@>
 
The ``banner line'' defined here should be changed whenever \.{ATANGLE} is
modified.
 
@d banner=="This is ATANGLE, Version 1.0"

@ The program consists of several packages that are declared right now;
each of these packages and either the specification and the body of
the packages are send to a seperate file. The main program itself
is declared later.

@ The first package we declare is called |int_number_io| and enables us
to output integer numbers. Further we declare a package |data_structures|,
which will contain all the global constants, types, variables, and some
procedures used throughout the program; it will (nearly) contain code of 
the sections ``The character set,'' ``Data structures,'' and ``Tokens.''

@a@~data_str.a@>
@.data_str.a@>
with TEXT_IO;
package @!int_number_io is new TEXT_IO.INTEGER_IO(INTEGER);
with TEXT_IO;
package data_structures is
  @<Types and objects visible from |data_structures|@>@;
  @<Specification of procedures visible from |data_structures|@>@;
end data_structures;
@#
@~data_str_b.a@>
@.data_str_b.a@>
with input_output; use input_output;
package body data_structures is
  @<Procedures in |data_structures|@>@;
begin
  @<Set initial values@>@;
end data_structures;

@ The following package, called |input_output|, is responsible for the
input/output features neaded by \.{ATANGLE}, and for the error handling.
It will contain code of sections ``Input and output'' and ``Reporting
errors to the user.''

@a
@~in_out.a@>
@.in_out.a@>
with TEXT_IO;
with data_structures; use data_structures;
package input_output is
  @<Specification of procedures visible from |input_output|@>@;
end input_output;
@#
@~in_out_b.a@>
@.in_out_b.a@>
with TEXT_IO,int_number_io;
package body input_output is
  @<Procedures in |input_output|@>@;
end input_output;

@ Additionally we have a package |hashing|, which contains the code of
sections ``Searching for identifiers''
and ``Searching for module names.''

@a
@~hash.a@>
@.hash.a@>
with data_structures; use data_structures;
package hashing is
  @<Specification of procedures visible from |hashing|@>@;
end hashing;
@#
@~hash_b.a@>
@.hash_b.a@>
with TEXT_IO;
with input_output; use input_output;
package body hashing is
  @<Procedures in |hashing|@>@;
end hashing;

@ The first of the two major packages will manage the output process of
\.{ATANGLE} and contains code of sections ``Stacks for output,''
``Producing the output,'' and ``The big output switch.''

@a
@~out_phase.a@>
@.out_phase.a@>
with data_structures; use data_structures;
package output_phase is
  procedure phase_ii;
end output_phase;
@#
@~out_phase_b.a@>
@.out_phase_b.a@>
with TEXT_IO,int_number_io;
with input_output; use input_output;
package body output_phase is
  @<Procedures in |output_phase|@>@;
end output_phase;

@ The last package will handle \.{ATANGLE}'s input process and contains code
of sections ``Introduction to the input phase,'' ``Inputting the next
token,'' ``Scanning a macro definition,'' and ``Scanning a module.''

@a
@~in_phase.a@>
@.in_phase.a@>
with data_structures; use data_structures;
with hashing; use hashing;
package input_phase is
  procedure phase_i;
end input_phase;
@#
@~in_phase_b.a@>
@.in_phase_b.a@>
with TEXT_IO,int_number_io;
with input_output; use input_output;
package body input_phase is
  @<Procedures in |input_phase|@>@;
end input_phase;

@ Some of this code, delimited by |stat| and |tats|, is optionally
included if statistics about \.{ATANGLE}'s memory usage are desired.
Other material is optionally included when a somewhat optimal code is
wanted; such is delimited by |optim| and |mitpo|.
 
@d stat==@{ {change this to `$\\{stat}\equiv\null$'
  when gathering usage statistics}
@d tats==@t@>@} {change this to `$\\{tats}\equiv\null$'
  when gathering usage statistics}
@f stat==declare
@f tats==end
@d optim==@{     {change this to `$\\{optim}\equiv\null$' when optimal
		  code is desired}
@d mitpo==@t@>@} {change this to `$\\{mitpo}\equiv\null$' when optimal
		  code is desired}
@f optim==declare
@f mitpo==end
 
@ Here are some macros for common programming idioms.
 
@d incr(#)  == #:=#+1@; {increase a variable by unity}
@d decr(#)  == #:=#-1@; {decrease a variable by unity}
@d repeat   == loop
@d until(#) == exit when #; end loop@;
@f repeat   == loop
@f until    == end
 
@ The following parameters are set big enough to handle \TeX, so they
should be sufficient for most applications of \.{ATANGLE}.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!buf_size:constant := 132; {maximum length of input line}
@!max_bytes:constant := 65_000; {|1/ww| times the number of bytes in 
	  identifiers, strings, and module names; must be less than |65_536|}
@!max_toks:constant := 65_000; {|1/zz| times the number of bytes in 
			   compressed \ADA\ code; must be less than |65_536|}
@!max_names:constant := 10_000; {number of identifiers, strings, module names;
				must be less than |10_240|}
@!max_texts:constant := 10_000; {number of replacement texts, must be less 
				than |10_240|}
@!hash_size:constant := 353; {should be prime}
@!longest_name:constant := 400; {module names shouldn't be longer than this}
@!line_length:constant := 132; {lines of \ADA\ output have at most this many 
                               characters}
@!out_buf_size:constant := 264; {length of output buffer, should be twice 
                                 |line_length|}
@!stack_size:constant := 50; {number of simultaneous levels of macro 
                              expansion}
@!max_id_length:constant := line_length; {long identifiers are chopped to 
                            this length, which must not exceed |line_length|}
@!unambig_length:constant := max_id_length; {identifiers must be unique if 
                                             chopped to this length}

@ A global variable called |history| will contain one of four values
at the end of every run: |spotless| means that no unusual messages were
printed; |harmless_message| means that a message of possible interest
was printed but no serious errors were detected; |error_message| means that
at least one error was found; |fatal_message| means that the program
terminated abnormally. The value of |history| does not influence the
behavior of the program; it is simply computed for the convenience
of systems that might want to use such information.
 
@d mark_harmless==if history=spotless then history:=harmless_message; 
                        end if@;
@d mark_error==history:=error_message@;
@d mark_fatal==history:=fatal_message@;
 
@<Types...@>=
type history_type is (@!spotless,@!harmless_message,@!error_message,
		      @!fatal_message);
@!history:history_type:=spotless; {how bad was this run?}

@* The character set.
One of the main goals in the design of \.{AWEB} has been to make it readily
portable between a wide variety of computers. Yet \.{AWEB} by its very
nature must use a greater variety of characters than most computer
programs deal with, and character encoding is one of the areas in which
existing machines differ most widely from each other.
 
To resolve this problem, all input to \.{AWEAVE} and \.{ATANGLE} is converted
to an internal seven-bit code that is essentially standard ASCII, the 
``American Standard Code for Information Interchange.''  The conversion is 
done immediately when each character is read in. Conversely, characters are
converted from ASCII to the user's external representation just before
they are output.
 
Such an internal code is relevant to users of \.{AWEB} only because it is
the code used for preprocessed constants like \.{@@'A'}. If you are
writing a program in \.{AWEB} that makes use of such one-character constants,
you should convert your input to ASCII form, like \.{AWEAVE} and \.{ATANGLE}
do. Otherwise \.{AWEB}'s internal coding scheme does not affect you.
@^ASCII code@>
 
Here is a table of the standard visible ASCII codes:
$$\def\:{\char\count255\global\advance\count255 by 1}
\count255='40
\vbox{
\hbox{\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill0\/\hfill}%
\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill1\/\hfill}%
\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill2\/\hfill}%
\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill3\/\hfill}%
\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill4\/\hfill}%
\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill5\/\hfill}%
\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill6\/\hfill}%
\hbox to 40pt{\it\hfill7\/\hfill}}
\vskip 4pt
\hrule
\def\^{\vrule height 10.5pt depth 4.5pt}
\halign{\hbox to 0pt{\hskip -24pt\bn{8}{#0}\hfill}&\^
\hbox to 40pt{\tt\hfill#\hfill\^}&
&\hbox to 40pt{\tt\hfill#\hfill\^}\cr
04&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
05&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
06&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
07&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
10&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
11&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
12&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
13&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
14&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
15&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
16&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr\noalign{\hrule}
17&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:&\:\cr}
\hrule width 280pt}$$
(Actually, of course, code \bn{8}{40} is an invisible blank space.)  Code
\bn{8}{136} was once an upward arrow (\.{\char'13}), and code \bn{8}{137} was
once a left arrow (\.^^X), in olden times when the first draft
of ASCII code was prepared; but \.{AWEB} works with today's standard
ASCII in which those codes represent circumflex and underline as shown.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!subtype ASCII_code is INTEGER range 0..127; {seven-bit numbers, a subrange
                                               of the integers}
 
@ We shall use the name |text_char| to stand for the data type of the 
characters in the input and output files.  We shall also assume that 
|text_char| consists of the elements |text_char'FIRST|
through  |text_char'LAST|, inclusive. The following
definition should be adjusted if necessary.
@^system dependencies@>
@^ADA attributes@>
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype text_char is CHARACTER; {the data type of characters in text files}
subtype text_file is TEXT_IO.FILE_TYPE; {file type consisting of |text_char|}

 
@ The \.{AWEAVE} and \.{ATANGLE} processors convert between ASCII code and
the user's external character set by means of arrays |xord| and |xchr|
that are analogous to \ADA's |POS| and |VAL| attributes.
@^ADA attributes@>
 
@<Types...@>=
@!xord: array (text_char) of ASCII_code;
  {specifies conversion of input characters}
@!xchr: array (ASCII_code) of text_char;
  {specifies conversion of output characters}
 
@ If we assume that every system using \.{AWEB} is able to read and write the
visible characters of standard ASCII (although not necessarily using the
ASCII codes to represent them), the following assignment statements 
initialize most of the |xchr| array properly, without needing any 
system-dependent changes. For example, the statement 
\.{xchr(8\#101\#):='A';} that appears in the present \.{AWEB} file might be
encoded in, say, {\mc EBCDIC} code on the external medium on which it 
resides, but \.{ATANGLE} will convert from this external code to ASCII and
back again. Therefore the assignment statement \.{XCHR(8\#101\#):='A';}
will appear in the corresponding \ADA\ file, and \ADA\ will compile this 
statement so that |xchr(8#101#)| receives  the character \.A in the external 
(|text_char|) code. Note that it would be quite incorrect to say
\.{xchr(8\#101\#):=@@'A';}, because |@'A'| is a constant of type
|INTEGER|, not |CHARACTER|, and because we have |@'A'=65| regardless of the
external character set.
 
@<Set init...@>=
xchr(8#40#):=' ';
xchr(8#41#):='!';
xchr(8#42#):='"';
xchr(8#43#):='#';
xchr(8#44#):='$';
xchr(8#45#):='%';
xchr(8#46#):='&';
xchr(8#47#):=''';@/
xchr(8#50#):='(';
xchr(8#51#):=')';
xchr(8#52#):='*';
xchr(8#53#):='+';
xchr(8#54#):=',';
xchr(8#55#):='-';
xchr(8#56#):='.';
xchr(8#57#):='/';@/
xchr(8#60#):='0';
xchr(8#61#):='1';
xchr(8#62#):='2';
xchr(8#63#):='3';
xchr(8#64#):='4';
xchr(8#65#):='5';
xchr(8#66#):='6';
xchr(8#67#):='7';@/
xchr(8#70#):='8';
xchr(8#71#):='9';
xchr(8#72#):=':';
xchr(8#73#):=';';
xchr(8#74#):='<';
xchr(8#75#):='=';
xchr(8#76#):='>';
xchr(8#77#):='?';@/
xchr(8#100#):='@@';
xchr(8#101#):='A';
xchr(8#102#):='B';
xchr(8#103#):='C';
xchr(8#104#):='D';
xchr(8#105#):='E';
xchr(8#106#):='F';
xchr(8#107#):='G';@/
xchr(8#110#):='H';
xchr(8#111#):='I';
xchr(8#112#):='J';
xchr(8#113#):='K';
xchr(8#114#):='L';
xchr(8#115#):='M';
xchr(8#116#):='N';
xchr(8#117#):='O';@/
xchr(8#120#):='P';
xchr(8#121#):='Q';
xchr(8#122#):='R';
xchr(8#123#):='S';
xchr(8#124#):='T';
xchr(8#125#):='U';
xchr(8#126#):='V';
xchr(8#127#):='W';@/
xchr(8#130#):='X';
xchr(8#131#):='Y';
xchr(8#132#):='Z';
xchr(8#133#):='[';
xchr(8#134#):='\';
xchr(8#135#):=']';
xchr(8#136#):='^';
xchr(8#137#):='_';@/
xchr(8#140#):='`';
xchr(8#141#):='a';
xchr(8#142#):='b';
xchr(8#143#):='c';
xchr(8#144#):='d';
xchr(8#145#):='e';
xchr(8#146#):='f';
xchr(8#147#):='g';@/
xchr(8#150#):='h';
xchr(8#151#):='i';
xchr(8#152#):='j';
xchr(8#153#):='k';
xchr(8#154#):='l';
xchr(8#155#):='m';
xchr(8#156#):='n';
xchr(8#157#):='o';@/
xchr(8#160#):='p';
xchr(8#161#):='q';
xchr(8#162#):='r';
xchr(8#163#):='s';
xchr(8#164#):='t';
xchr(8#165#):='u';
xchr(8#166#):='v';
xchr(8#167#):='w';@/
xchr(8#170#):='x';
xchr(8#171#):='y';
xchr(8#172#):='z';
xchr(8#173#):='{';
xchr(8#174#):='|';
xchr(8#175#):='}';
xchr(8#176#):='~';@/
xchr(0):=' '; xchr(8#177#):=' '; {these ASCII codes are not used}
 
@ Some of the ASCII codes below \bn{8}{40} have been given symbolic names in
\.{AWEAVE} and \.{ATANGLE} because they are used with a special meaning.
 
@<Types...@>=
and_sign : constant ASCII_code:=8#4#; {equivalent to `\.{and}'}
not_sign : constant ASCII_code:=8#5#; {equivalent to `\.{not}'}
set_element_sign : constant ASCII_code:=8#6#; {equivalent to `\.{in}'}
tab_mark : constant ASCII_code:=8#11#; {ASCII code used as tab-skip}
line_feed : constant ASCII_code:=8#12#; {ASCII code thrown away at end of line}
form_feed : constant ASCII_code:=8#14#; {ASCII code used at end of page}
carriage_return : constant ASCII_code:=8#15#; {ASCII code used at end of line}
right_arrow : constant ASCII_code:=8#21#; {equivalent to `\.{=>}'}
box_sign : constant ASCII_code:=8#22#; {equivalent to `\.{<>}'}
double_star : constant ASCII_code:=8#23#; {equivalent to `\.{**}'}
left_label_bracket:constant ASCII_code:=8#24#; {equivalent to `\.{<<}'}
right_label_bracket:constant ASCII_code:=8#25#; {equivalent to `\.{>>}'}
left_arrow : constant ASCII_code:=8#30#; {equivalent to `\.{:=}'}
not_equal : constant ASCII_code:=8#32#; {equivalent to `\.{/=}'}
less_or_equal : constant ASCII_code:=8#34#; {equivalent to `\.{<=}'}
greater_or_equal : constant ASCII_code:=8#35#; {equivalent to `\.{>=}'}
equivalence_sign : constant ASCII_code:=8#36#; {equivalent to `\.{==}'}
or_sign : constant ASCII_code:=8#37#; {equivalent to `\.{or}'}
 
@ Here now is the system-dependent part of the character set.
If \.{AWEB} is being implemented on a garden-variety \ADA\ for which
only standard ASCII codes will appear in the input and output files, you
don't need to make any changes here.
@^system dependencies@>
 
Changes to the present module will make \.{AWEB} more friendly on computers
that have an extended character set, so that one can type things like
\.^^Z\ instead of \.{/=}. If you have an extended set of characters that
are easily incorporated into text files, you can assign codes arbitrarily
here, giving an |xchr| equivalent to whatever characters the users of
\.{AWEB} are allowed to have in their input files, provided that unsuitable
characters do not correspond to special codes like |carriage_return|
that are listed above.
 
(The present file \.{ATANGLE.AWEB} does not contain any of the non-ASCII
characters, because it is intended to be used with all implementations of
\.{AWEB}.)
 
@<Set init...@>=
xchr(1..8#37#):=(others=>' ');
 
@ The following system-independent code makes the |xord| array contain a
suitable inverse to the information in |xchr|.
 
@<Set init...@>=
xord(text_char):=(others=>8#40#);
for i in 1..8#176# loop xord(xchr(i)):=i;  end loop;
 
@* Input and output.
The input conventions of this program are identical to those of \.{AWEAVE}.
Therefore people who need to make modifications to both systems
should be able to do so without too many headaches.
 
@ Terminal output is done by writing on file |STANDARD_OUTPUT|, which is
assumed to consist of characters of type |text_char|:
@^system dependencies@>
 
@d new_ln==TEXT_IO.NEW_LINE
@d print(#)==TEXT_IO.PUT(#) {`|print|' means write on the terminal}
@d print_ln(#)==print(#); new_ln {`|print|' and then start new line}
@d print_nl(#)==new_ln; print(#) {print information starting on a
                                          new line}
@d print_int(#)==int_number_io.PUT(#) {print out an integer value}

@ The |update_terminal| procedure is called when we want
to make sure that everything we have output to the terminal so far has
actually left the computer's internal buffers and been sent.
(In the \ADA-system used to develop the initial program this is not
required.)
@^system dependencies@>
 
@d update_terminal == null {empty the terminal output buffer}
 

@ The main input comes from |web_file|; this input may be overridden
by changes in |change_file|. 
(If |change_file| is empty, there are no changes.)
 
@<Types...@>=
@!web_file:text_file; {primary input}
@!change_file:text_file; {updates}
 
@ @<Specification of procedures visible from |input_output|@>=
procedure open_a_file(f:in out text_file;mode_of_file:TEXT_IO.FILE_MODE;
			default_name:STRING;success:out BOOLEAN);
function create_ada_file(ada_file_name:STRING)return BOOLEAN;

@ The following code opens a file and returns |TRUE| if succesfully.
If the file is already open the procedure has no effect; this gives
the ability to open the files by means of the change file, without
changing the \.{AWEB}-file of \.{ATANGLE}.
@^system dependencies@>
 

@<Procedures in |input_output|@>=
procedure @!open_a_file(@!f:in out text_file;
			@!mode_of_file:TEXT_IO.FILE_MODE;
			@!default_name:STRING;
			@!success:out BOOLEAN) is
begin if TEXT_IO.IS_OPEN(f) then success:=TRUE;
      else TEXT_IO.OPEN(FILE=>f,MODE=>mode_of_file,NAME=>default_name);
	   success:=TRUE;
      end if;
exception
  when @!@!TEXT_IO.STATUS_ERROR !
       @!@!TEXT_IO.NAME_ERROR !
       @!@!TEXT_IO.USE_ERROR     => success:=FALSE; return;
end open_a_file;
 
@ The main output goes to |ada_file|.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!ada_file: text_file;
 
@ The following code creates |ada_file|.
@^system dependencies@>
 
@<Procedures in |input_output|@>=
function @!create_ada_file(@!ada_file_name:STRING)return BOOLEAN is
begin if TEXT_IO.IS_OPEN(ada_file) then
	if TEXT_IO.NAME(ada_file)=ada_file_name then
	  return TRUE;
        else 
	  return FALSE;
        end if;
      else TEXT_IO.CREATE(FILE => ada_file,MODE => TEXT_IO.OUT_FILE ,
			  NAME => ada_file_name);
	   return TRUE;
      end if;
exception 
  when @!@!TEXT_IO.STATUS_ERROR !
       @!@!TEXT_IO.NAME_ERROR !
       @!@!TEXT_IO.USE_ERROR      => return FALSE;
end create_ada_file;

@ Input goes into an array called |buffer|.
@<Types...@>=type buffer_type is array(INTEGER range <>)of ASCII_code;
	     subtype buffer_index is INTEGER range 0..buf_size;
	     @!buffer: buffer_type(buffer_index);
 
@ The |input_ln| procedure brings the next line of input from the specified
file into the |buffer| array and returns the value |TRUE|, unless the file
has already been entirely read, in which case it returns |FALSE|. The
conventions of \TeX\ are followed; i.e., |ASCII_code| numbers representing 
the next line of the file are input into |buffer(0)|, |buffer(1)|, \dots,
|buffer(limit-1)|; trailing blanks are ignored; 
and the global variable |limit| is set to the length of the
@^system dependencies@>
line. The value of |limit| must be strictly less than |buf_size|.
 
We assume that none of the |ASCII_code| values
of |buffer(j)| for |0<=j<limit| is equal to 0, \bn{8}{177}, |line_feed|, 
|form_feed|, or |carriage_return|.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |input_output|@>=
function input_ln(f:text_file) return BOOLEAN;

@ @<Procedures in |input_output|@>=
function @!input_ln(@!f:text_file) return BOOLEAN is
  {inputs a line or returns |FALSE|}
@!final_limit:buffer_index:=0; {|limit| without trailing blanks}
@!c:text_char;
begin limit:=0;
if not TEXT_IO.IS_OPEN(f) or else TEXT_IO.END_OF_FILE(f) then return FALSE;
else  while not TEXT_IO.END_OF_LINE(f) loop
	TEXT_IO.GET(f,c);
        buffer(limit):=xord(c);
        incr(limit);
        if buffer(limit-1)/=@' ' then final_limit:=limit;
        end if;
        if limit=buf_size then
	  TEXT_IO.SKIP_LINE(f);
          decr(limit); {keep |buffer(buf_size)| empty}
          print_nl("! Input line too long"); loc:=0; error;
	  return TRUE;
@.Input line too long@>
      end if;
    end loop;
  TEXT_IO.SKIP_LINE(f); limit:=final_limit; return TRUE;
  end if;
end input_ln;



@* Reporting errors to the user.
The \.{ATANGLE} processor operates in two phases: first it inputs the source
file and stores a compressed representation of the program, then it produces
the \ADA\ output from the compressed representation.
 
The global variable |phase_one| tells whether we are in Phase I or not.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!phase_one: BOOLEAN; {|TRUE| in Phase I, |FALSE| in Phase II}
 
@ During the first phase, syntax errors are reported to the user by saying
$$\hbox{`|err_print("! Error message")|'},$$
followed by `|jump_out|' if no recovery from the error is provided.
This will print the error message followed by an indication of where the 
error was spotted in the source file. Note that no period follows the error 
message, since the error routine will automatically supply a period.
 
Errors that are noticed during the second phase are reported to the user
in the same fashion, but the error message will be
followed by an indication of where the error was spotted in the output file.
 
The actual error indications are provided by a procedure called |error|.
 
@d err_print(#)==print_nl(#); error@;
@<Specification of procedures visible from |input_output|@>=
procedure error;

@ @<Procedures in |input_output|@>=
procedure @!error is {prints '\..' and location of error message}
@!l:buffer_index; {index into |buffer|}
begin if phase_one then @<Print error location based on input buffer@>;
else @<Print error location based on output buffer@>;
end if;
update_terminal; mark_error;
end error;
 
@ The error locations during Phase I can be indicated by using the global
variables |loc|, |line|, and |changing|, which tell respectively the first
unlooked-at position in |buffer|, the current line number, and whether or not
the current line is from |change_file| or |web_file|.
This routine should be modified on systems whose standard text editor
has special line-numbering conventions.
@^system dependencies@>
 
@<Print error location based on input buffer@>=
if changing then print(". (change file "); else print(". ("); end if;
print("l.");
print_int(line,1);
print_ln(")");
if loc>=limit then l:=limit; else l:=loc; end if;
for k in 1..l loop
  if buffer(k-1)=tab_mark then print(" ");
  else print(xchr(buffer(k-1))); {print the characters already read}
  end if;
end loop;
new_ln;
for k in 1..l loop print(" "); end loop; {space out the next line}
for k in l+1..limit loop print(xchr(buffer(k-1))); end loop;
                  {print the part not yet read}
print(" ")@; {this space separates the message from future asterisks}
 
@ The position of errors detected during the second phase can be indicated
by outputting the partially-filled output buffer, which contains |out_ptr|
entries. The current output file name is determined by |file_name| and
|fn_length|, whereas the line number comes from |f_line|.
 
@<Print error location based on output...@>=
print(".("&file_name(1..fn_length)&" l.");
print_int(f_line,1);
print_ln(")");
for j in 1..out_ptr loop print(xchr(out_buf(j-1)));
{print current partial line}
end loop;
print("... ")@; {indicate that this information is partial}
 
@ The |jump_out| macro just raises the |end_of_ATANGLE| exception.
It is used when no recovery from a particular error has
been provided.
 
@d jump_out==raise end_of_ATANGLE@;
@d fatal_error(#)==print_nl(#); error; mark_fatal; jump_out@;
 
@<Types...@>= @!end_of_ATANGLE : exception;

@ Sometimes the program's behavior is far different from what it should be,
and \.{ATANGLE} prints an error message that is really for the \.{ATANGLE}
maintenance person, not the user. In such cases the program says
|confusion("indication of where we are")|.
 
@d confusion(#)==fatal_error("! This can't happen ("&#&")")
@.This can't happen@>
 
@ An overflow stop occurs if \.{ATANGLE}'s tables aren't large enough.
 
@d overflow(#)==fatal_error("! Sorry, "&#&" capacity exceeded")
@.Sorry, x capacity exceeded@>
 
 
@* Data structures.
Most of the user's \ADA\ code is packed into seven- or eight-bit integers
in two large arrays called |byte_mem| and |tok_mem|.
The |byte_mem| array holds the names of identifiers, strings, and modules;
the |tok_mem| array holds the replacement texts
for macros and modules. Allocation is sequential, since things are deleted 
only during Phase II, and only in a last-in-first-out manner.
 
Auxiliary arrays |byte_start| and |tok_start| are used as directories to
|byte_mem| and |tok_mem|, and the |link|, |ilk|, |equiv|, and |text_link|
arrays give further information about names. These auxiliary arrays
consist of sixteen-bit items.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!subtype eight_bits is INTEGER range 0..255; {unsigned one-byte quantity}
@!subtype sixteen_bits is INTEGER range 0..65_535; {unsigned two-byte
                                                    quantity}

@ \.{ATANGLE} has been designed to avoid the need for indices that are more
than sixteen bits wide, so that it can be used on most computers. But
there are programs that need more than 65536 tokens, and some programs
even need more than 65536 bytes; \TeX\ is one of these.  To get around
this problem, a slight complication has been added to the data structures:
|byte_mem| and |tok_mem| are two-dimensional arrays, whose first index is
either 0 or 1. (For generality, the first index is actually allowed to run
between 0 and |ww-1| in |byte_mem|, or between 0 and |zz-1| in |tok_mem|,
where |ww| and |zz| are set to 2 and~3; the program will work for any
positive values of |ww| and |zz|, and it can be simplified in obvious ways
if |ww=1| or |zz=1|.)

@<Types...@>=
@!ww : constant INTEGER := 2;
@!zz : constant INTEGER := 3;
@#
subtype w_range is INTEGER range 0..ww-1;
subtype z_range is INTEGER range 0..zz-1;
subtype byte_index is INTEGER range 0..max_bytes;
subtype token_index is INTEGER range 0..max_toks;
subtype name_index is INTEGER range 0..max_names;
subtype text_index is INTEGER range 0..max_texts;
@#
type byte_memory is array(w_range,byte_index) of ASCII_code;
optim pragma PACK(byte_memory); mitpo@;
@#
type token_memory is array(z_range,token_index) of eight_bits;
optim pragma PACK(token_memory); mitpo@;
@#
type name_info is array(name_index) of sixteen_bits;
type token_info is array(text_index) of sixteen_bits;
@#
@!byte_mem: byte_memory; {characters of names}
@!tok_mem: token_memory; {tokens}
@!byte_start: name_info; {directory into |byte_mem|}
@!tok_start: token_info; {directory into |tok_mem|}
@!link: name_info; {hash table or tree links}
@!ilk: name_info; {type codes or tree links}
@!equiv: name_info; {info corresponding to names}
@!text_link: token_info; {relates replacement texts}
 
@ The names of identifiers are found by computing a hash address |h| and
then looking at strings of bytes signified by |hash(h)|, |link(hash(h))|,
|link(link(hash(h)))|, \dots, until either finding the desired name
or encountering a zero.
 
A `|name_pointer|' variable, which signifies a name, is an index into
|byte_start|. The actual sequence of characters in the name pointed to by
|p| appears in positions |byte_start(p)| to |byte_start(p+ww)-1|, inclusive,
in the segment of |byte_mem| whose first index is |p mod ww|. Thus, when
|ww=2| the even-numbered name bytes appear in |byte_mem(0,@t$*$@>)|
and the odd-numbered ones appear in |byte_mem(1,@t$*$@>)|.
The pointer 0 is used for undefined module names; we don't
want to use it for the names of identifiers, since 0 stands for a null
pointer in a linked list.
 
The total number of names in |byte_mem|
is called |name_ptr| and the total number of bytes occupied in
|byte_mem(w,@t$*$@>)| is called |byte_ptr(w)|.
 
We usually have |byte_start(name_ptr+w)=byte_ptr((name_ptr+w) mod ww)|
for |0<=w<ww|, since these are the starting positions for the next |ww|
names to be stored in |byte_mem|.
 
@d length(#)==byte_start(#+ww)-byte_start(#) {the length of a name}
@d null_array==(others=>0)
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype name_pointer is name_index; {identifies a name}
@#
@!name_ptr:name_pointer:=1; {first unused position in |byte_start|}
@!byte_ptr:array (w_range) of byte_index:=null_array;
    {first unused position in |byte_mem|}

@ @<Set init...@>=
byte_start(0..ww):=null_array; {this makes name 0 of length zero}
 
@ Replacement texts are stored in |tok_mem|, using similar conventions.
A `|text_pointer|' variable is an index into |tok_start|, and the
replacement text that corresponds to |p| runs from positions
|tok_start(p)| to |tok_start(p+zz)-1|, inclusive, in the segment of
|tok_mem| whose first index is |p mod zz|. Thus, when |zz=2| the
even-numbered replacement texts appear in |tok_mem(0,@t$*$@>)| and the
odd-numbered ones appear in |tok_mem(1,@t$*$@>)|.  Furthermore,
|text_link(p)| is used to connect pieces of text that have the same name,
as we shall see later. The pointer 0 is used for undefined replacement
texts.
 
The first position of |tok_mem(z,@t$*$@>)| that is unoccupied by
replacement text is called |tok_ptr(z)|, and the first unused location of
|tok_start| is called |text_ptr|.  We usually have the identity
|tok_start(text_ptr+z)=tok_ptr((text_ptr+z) mod zz)|, for |0<=z<zz|, since
these are the starting positions for the next |zz| replacement texts to
be stored in |tok_mem|.

It is convenient to maintain a variable |z| that is equal to |text_ptr
mod zz|, so that we always insert tokens into segment |z| of |tok_mem|.
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype text_pointer is text_index; {identifies a replacement text}
@#
@!text_ptr:text_pointer:=1; {first unused position in |tok_start|}
@!tok_ptr:array(z_range) of token_index:=null_array;
  {first unused position in a given segment of |tok_mem|}
@!z:z_range:=1 mod zz; {current segment of |tok_mem|}
stat @!max_tok_ptr:array(z_range) of token_index;
  {largest values assumed by |tok_ptr|}
tats@;
 
@ @<Set init...@>=
  tok_start(0..zz):=null_array;
  {this makes replacement text 0 of length zero}
 
@ Three types of identifiers are distinguished by their |ilk|:
 
\yskip\hang |normal| identifiers will appear in the \ADA\ program as
ordinary identifiers since they have not been defined to be macros; the
corresponding value in the |equiv| array for such identifiers is a link in a 
secondary hash table that is used to check whether any two of them agree in 
their first |unambig_length| characters after letters are changed to 
uppercase.
 
\yskip\hang |simple| identifiers have been defined to be simple macros;
their |equiv| value points to the corresponding replacement text.
 
\yskip\hang |parametric| identifiers have been defined to be parametric 
macros; like simple identifiers, their |equiv| value points to the 
replacement text.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!normal: constant sixteen_bits := 0; {ordinary identifiers have |normal| ilk}
@!simple: constant sixteen_bits := 1; {simple macros have |simple| ilk}
@!parametric: constant sixteen_bits :=2; {parametric macros have |parametric| ilk}
 
@ The names of modules are stored in |byte_mem| together with the identifier 
names, but a hash table is not used for them because \.{ATANGLE} needs to be
able to recognize a module name when given a prefix of that name. A 
conventional binary seach tree is used to retrieve module names, with fields 
called |llink| and |rlink| in place of |link| and |ilk|. The root of this 
tree is |rlink(0)|. If |p| is a pointer to a module name, |equiv(p)| points 
to its replacement text, just as in simple and parametric macros, unless this 
replacement text has not yet been defined (in which case |equiv(p)=0|).
 
@<Types...@>=
@!llink:name_info renames link; {left link in binary search tree for module names}
@!rlink:name_info renames ilk; {right link in binary search tree for module names}
 
@ @<Set init...@>=
rlink(0):=0; {the binary search tree starts out with nothing in it}
equiv(0):=0; {the undefined module has no replacement text}
 
@ Here is a little procedure that prints the text of a given name.
@<Specification of procedures visible from |data_structures|@>=
  procedure print_id(p:name_pointer);

@ @<Procedures in |data_structures|@>=
procedure @!print_id(@!p:name_pointer)is {print identifier or module name}
@!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
begin if p>=name_ptr then print("IMPOSSIBLE");
else  w:=p mod ww;
  for k in byte_start(p)..byte_start(p+ww)-1 loop
      print(xchr(byte_mem(w,k)));
  end loop;
end if;
end print_id;

@* Searching for identifiers.
The hash table described above is updated by the |id_lookup| procedure,
which finds a given identifier and returns a pointer to its index in
|byte_start|. If the identifier was not already present, it is inserted with
a given |ilk| code; and an error message is printed if the identifier is 
being doubly defined.
 
Because of the way \.{ATANGLE}'s scanning mechanism works, it is most
convenient to let |id_lookup| search for an identifier that is present in the 
|buffer| array. Two other global variables specify its position in the 
buffer: the first character is |buffer(id_first)|, and the last is 
|buffer(id_loc-1)|.
 
We have mentioned that |normal| identifiers belong to two hash tables, one 
for their true names as they appear in the \.{AWEB} file and the other when
they have been reduced to their first |unambig_length| characters. The hash 
tables are kept by the method of simple chaining, where the heads of the 
individual lists appear in the |hash| and |chop_hash| arrays. If |h| is a 
hash code, the primary hash table list starts at |hash(h)| and proceeds 
through |link| pointers; the secondary hash table list starts at 
|chop_hash(h)| and proceeds through |equiv| pointers. Of course, the same
identifier will probably have two different values of |h|.
 
The |id_lookup| procedure uses an auxiliary array called |chopped_id| to
contain up to |unambig_length| characters of the current identifier, if
it is necessary to compute the secondary hash code. 
 
@<Types...@>=
@!id_first:buffer_index; {where the current identifier begins in the buffer}
@!id_loc:buffer_index; {just after the current identifier in the buffer}
@#
subtype hash_index is INTEGER range 0..hash_size;
subtype chop_hash_index is INTEGER range 0..unambig_length;
@!hash,@!chop_hash:array (hash_index) of sixteen_bits:=null_array;
	      {heads of hash lists---initially empty}
@!chopped_id:array (chop_hash_index) of ASCII_code; {chopped identifier}

 
 
@ Here now is the main procedure for finding identifiers (and strings).
The parameter |t| is set to |normal| except when the identifier is
a macro name that is just being defined; in the latter case, |t| will be
|simple| or |parametric|.

@<Specification of procedures visible from |hashing|@>=
  function id_lookup(t:eight_bits)return name_pointer;

@ @<Procedures in |hashing|@>=
function @!id_lookup(@!t:eight_bits)return name_pointer is {finds current
							    identifier}
@!c:eight_bits; {byte being chopped}
@!i:buffer_index; {index into |buffer|}
@!h:hash_index; {hash code}
@!k:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
@!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
@!l:buffer_index:=id_loc-id_first; {length of the given identifier}
@!p,@!q:name_pointer; {where the identifier is being sought}
@!s:chop_hash_index; {index into |chopped_id|}
begin
@<Compute the hash code |h|@>;
@<Compute the name location |p|@>;
if (p=name_ptr)or(t/=normal) then
  @<Update the tables and check for possible errors@>;
end if;
return p;
end id_lookup;
 
@ A simple hash code is used: If the sequence of
ASCII codes is $c_1c_2\ldots c_n$, its hash value will be
$$(2^{n-1}c_1+2^{n-2}c_2+\cdots+c_n)\,\bmod\,|hash_size|.$$
 
@<Compute the hash...@>=
h:=buffer(id_first); i:=id_first+1;
while i<id_loc loop
  h:=(h+h+buffer(i)) mod hash_size; incr(i);
  end loop@;
 
@ If the identifier is new, it will be placed in position |p=name_ptr|,
otherwise |p| will point to its existing location.
 
@<Compute the name location...@>=
p:=hash(h);
while p/=0 loop
  if length(p)=l then
      @<Compare name |p| with current identifier, |goto found| if equal@>;
    end if;
  p:=link(p);
  end loop;
p:=name_ptr; {the current identifier is new}
link(p):=hash(h); hash(h):=p; {insert |p| at beginning of hash list}
<<found>> null@;
 
@ @<Compare name |p|...@>=
i:=id_first; k:=byte_start(p); w:=p mod ww;
while (i<id_loc)and(buffer(i)=byte_mem(w,k)) loop
  incr(i); incr(k);
  end loop;
if i=id_loc then goto found; {all characters agree}
end if@;

@ @<Update the tables...@>=
if ((p/=name_ptr)and(t/=normal)and(ilk(p)=normal)) or
    ((p=name_ptr)and(t=normal)) then
  @<Compute the secondary hash code |h| and put the first characters
  into the auxiliary array |chopped_id|@>;
end if;
if p/=name_ptr then @<Give double-definition error and change |p|
                      to type |t|@>;
else @<Enter a new identifier into the table at position |p|@>;
end if@;
 
@ The following routine, which is called into play when it is necessary to
look at the secondary hash table, computes the same hash function as before
(but on the chopped data), and places a zero after the chopped identifier
in |chopped_id| to serve as a convenient sentinel.
@^uppercase@>
 
@<Compute the secondary...@>=
i:=id_first; s:=0; h:=0;
while (i<id_loc)and(s<unambig_length) loop
  if buffer(i)>=@'a' then chopped_id(s):=buffer(i)-8#40#;
  else chopped_id(s):=buffer(i);
  end if;
  h:=(h+h+chopped_id(s)) mod hash_size; incr(s);
  incr(i);
  end loop;
chopped_id(s):=0@;
 
@ If a macro has appeared before it was defined, \.{ATANGLE} will still work
all right; after all, such behavior is typical of the replacement texts for 
modules, which act very much like macros. However, \.{ATANGLE} finds it
simplest to make a blanket rule that macros should be defined before they are 
used. The following routine gives an error message and also fixes up any 
damage that may have been caused.
 
@<Give double...@>= {now |p/=name_ptr| and |t/=normal|}
if ilk(p)=normal then
  err_print("! This identifier has already appeared");@/
@.This identifier has already...@>
  @<Remove |p| from secondary hash table@>;
else err_print("! This identifier was defined before");
@.This identifier was defined...@>
end if;
ilk(p):=t@;
 
@ When we have to remove a secondary hash entry, because a |normal| 
identifier is changing to another |ilk|, the hash code |h| and chopped 
identifier have already been computed.
 
@<Remove |p| from secondary...@>=
q:=chop_hash(h);
if q=p then chop_hash(h):=equiv(p);
else while equiv(q)/=p loop q:=equiv(q); end loop;
  equiv(q):=equiv(p);
end if@;
 
@ @<Enter a new identifier...@>=
if t=normal then
  @<Check for ambiguity and update secondary hash@>;
end if;
w:=name_ptr mod ww; k:=byte_ptr(w);
if k+l>max_bytes then overflow("byte memory"); end if;
if name_ptr>max_names-ww then overflow("name"); end if;
i:=id_first; {get ready to move the identifier into |byte_mem|}
while i<id_loc loop
  byte_mem(w,k):=buffer(i); incr(k); incr(i);
  end loop;
byte_ptr(w):=k; byte_start(name_ptr+ww):=k; incr(name_ptr); ilk(p):=t@;

 
@ @<Check for ambig...@>=
q:=chop_hash(h);
while q/=0 loop
  @<Check if |q| conflicts with |p|@>;
  q:=equiv(q);
  end loop;
equiv(p):=chop_hash(h); chop_hash(h):=p@;{put |p| at front of secondary list}
 
@ @<Check if |q| conflicts...@>=
k:=byte_start(q); s:=0; w:=q mod ww;
while (k<byte_start(q+ww)) and (s<unambig_length) loop
  c:=byte_mem(w,k);
  if c>=@'a' then c:=c-8#40#; {convert to uppercase}
@^uppercase@>
  end if;
  if chopped_id(s)/=c then goto not_found;
  end if;
  incr(s);
  incr(k);
  end loop;
if (k=byte_start(q+ww))and(chopped_id(s)/=0) then goto not_found;
end if;
print_nl("! Identifier conflict with ");
@.Identifier conflict...@>
for kl in byte_start(q)..byte_start(q+ww)-1 loop print(xchr(byte_mem(w,kl)));
end loop;
error; q:=0; {only one conflict will be printed, since |equiv(0)=0|}
<<not_found>> null@;
 
@* Searching for module names.
The |mod_lookup| procedure finds the module name |mod_text(1..l)| in the
search tree, after inserting it if necessary, and returns a pointer to
where it was found.
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype long_name_index is INTEGER range 0..longest_name;
@!mod_text:array (long_name_index) of ASCII_code; {name being sought for}
 
@ According to the rules of \.{AWEB}, no module name should be a proper prefix
of another, so a ``clean'' comparison should occur between any two names. The 
result of |mod_lookup| is 0 if this prefix condition is violated. An error 
message is printed when such violations are detected during phase two of 
\.{AWEAVE}.
 
@<Types...@>=
type compare is (@!less,@!equal,@!greater,@!prefix,@!extension);
 
@ @<Specification of procedures visible from |hashing|@>=
  function mod_lookup(l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer;

@ @<Procedures in |hashing|@>=
function @!mod_lookup(@!l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer is 
      {finds module name}
@!c:compare:=greater; {comparison between two names}
@!j:long_name_index; {index into |mod_text|}
@!k:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
@!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
@!p:name_pointer; {current node of the search tree}
@!q:name_pointer:=0; {father of node |p|}
begin p:=rlink(0); {|rlink(0)| is the root of the tree}
while p/=0 loop
  @<Set \(|c| to the result of comparing the given name to
    name |p|@>;
  q:=p;
  if c=less then p:=llink(q);
  elsif c=greater then p:=rlink(q);
  else goto found;
  end if;
  end loop;
@<Enter a new module name into the tree@>;
<<found>> if c/=equal then
  err_print("! Incompatible section names"); @/ p:=0;
@.Incompatible module names@>
  end if;
return p;
end mod_lookup;
 
@ @<Enter a new module name...@>=
w:=name_ptr mod ww; k:=byte_ptr(w);
if k+l>max_bytes then overflow("byte memory");
end if;
if name_ptr>max_names-ww then overflow("name");
end if;
p:=name_ptr;
if c=less then llink(q):=p; else rlink(q):=p;
end if;
llink(p):=0; rlink(p):=0; c:=equal; equiv(p):=0;
for kj in 1..l loop byte_mem(w,k+kj-1):=mod_text(kj);
end loop;
byte_ptr(w):=k+l; byte_start(name_ptr+ww):=k+l; incr(name_ptr)@;
 
@ @<Set \(|c|...@>=
k:=byte_start(p); w:=p mod ww; c:=equal; j:=1;
while (k<byte_start(p+ww)) and (j<=l) and (mod_text(j)=byte_mem(w,k)) loop
  incr(k); incr(j);
  end loop;
if k=byte_start(p+ww) then
  if j>l then c:=equal;
  else c:=extension;
  end if;
elsif j>l then c:=prefix;
elsif mod_text(j)<byte_mem(w,k) then c:=less;
else c:=greater;
end if@;
 
@ The |prefix_lookup| procedure is supposed to find exactly one module
name that has |mod_text(1..l)| as a prefix. Actually the algorithm silently
accepts also the situation that some module name is a prefix of
|mod_text(1..l)|, because the user who painstakingly typed in more than
necessary probably doesn't want to be told about the wasted effort.
 
@<Specification of procedures visible from |hashing|@>=
  function prefix_lookup(l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer;

@ @<Procedures in |hashing|@>=
function @!prefix_lookup(@!l:sixteen_bits)return name_pointer is 
     {finds name extension}
@!c:compare; {comparison between two names}
@!count:name_index:=0; {the number of hits}
@!j:long_name_index; {index into |mod_text|}
@!k:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
@!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
@!p:name_pointer; {current node of the search tree}
@!q:name_pointer:=0; {another place to resume the search after one
		      branch is done}
@!r:name_pointer:=0; {extension found}
begin p:=rlink(0); {begin search at root of tree}
while p/=0 loop
  @<Set \(|c|...@>;
  if c=less then p:=llink(p);
  elsif c=greater then p:=rlink(p);
  else  r:=p; incr(count); q:=rlink(p); p:=llink(p);
    end if;
  if p=0 then
    p:=q; q:=0;
    end if;
  end loop;
if count/=1 then
  if count=0 then err_print("! Name does not match");
@.Name does not match@>
  else err_print("! Ambiguous prefix");
@.Ambiguous prefix@>
  end if;
end if;
return r; {the result will be 0 if there was no match}
end prefix_lookup;
 
@* Tokens.
Replacement texts, which represent \ADA\ code in a compressed format, appear 
in |tok_mem| as mentioned above. The codes in these texts are called 
`tokens'; some tokens occupy two consecutive eight-bit byte positions, and 
the others take just one byte.
 
If $p>0$ points to a replacement text, |tok_start(p)| is the |tok_mem| 
position of the first eight-bit code of that text. If |text_link(p)=0|,
this is the replacement text for a macro, otherwise it is the replacement
text for a module. In the latter case |text_link(p)| is either equal to
|module_flag|, which means that there is no further text for this module, or
|text_link(p)| points to a continuation of this replacement text; such links 
are created when several modules have \ADA\ texts with the same name, and 
they also tie together all the \ADA\ texts of unnamed modules. The 
replacement text pointer for the first unnamed module appears in 
|text_link(0)|, and the most recent such pointer is |last_unnamed|.
 
@<Types...@>=
module_flag:constant sixteen_bits:=max_texts; {final |link| in module replacement texts}
@!last_unnamed:text_pointer:=0; {most recent replacement text of unnamed module}
 
@ @<Set init...@>=text_link(0):=0;
 
@ If the first byte of a token is less than |8#200#|, the token occupies a
single byte. Otherwise we make a sixteen-bit token by combining two 
consecutive bytes |a| and |b|. If |8#200#<=a<8#250#|, then 
$(a-\bn{8}{200})\times2^8+b$ points to an identifier; if |8#250#<=a<8#320#|, 
then $(a-\bn{8}{250})\times2^8+b$ points to a module name; otherwise, i.e., 
if |8#320#<=a<8#400#|, then $(a-\bn{8}{320})\times2^8+b$ is the number of the 
module in which the current replacement text appears.
 
Codes less than \bn{8}{200} are 7-bit ASCII codes that represent themselves.
In particular, a single-character identifier like `|x|' will be a one-byte
token, while all longer identifiers will occupy two bytes.
 
Some of the 7-bit ASCII codes will not be present, however, so we can
use them for special purposes. The following symbolic names are used:
 
\yskip\hang |param| denotes insertion of a parameter. This occurs only in
the replacement texts of parametric macros, outside of single-quoted strings
in those texts.
 
\hang |begin_comment| denotes \.{@@\{}, which will become \.{--}.
 
\hang |end_comment| denotes \.{@@\}}, which will become a new line.
 
\hang |character_tok| denotes the \.' that encloses an character constant.
 
\hang |ascii_tok| denotes the \.{@@'} that precedes a ASCII code constant.
@^ASCII code constant@>
 
\hang |output_tok| denotes the \.{@@\~} that precedes an output file-name.

\hang |join| denotes the concatenation of adjacent items with no
space or line breaks allowed between them (the \.{@@\&} operation of \.{AWEB}).
 
\hang |double_dot| denotes `\.{..}' in \ADA.
 
\hang |verbatim| denotes the \.{@@=} that begins a verbatim \ADA\ string.
It is also used for the end of the string.
 
\hang |force_line| denotes the \.{@@\\} that forces a new line in the
\ADA\ output.
@^ASCII code@>
 
@<Types...@>=
@!param: constant eight_bits:=0; {ASCII null code will not appear}
@!verbatim: constant eight_bits:=2; {extended ASCII alpha should not appear}
@!force_line: constant eight_bits:=3; {extended ASCII beta should not appear}
@!begin_comment: constant eight_bits:=8#11#; {ASCII tab mark will not appear}
@!end_comment: constant eight_bits:=8#12#; {ASCII line feed will not appear}
@!character_tok: constant eight_bits:=8#14#; {ASCII form feed will not appear}
@!ascii_tok: constant eight_bits:=8#15#; {ASCII carriage return will not appear}
@!output_tok: constant eight_bits:=8#16#; {ASCII \.{DLE} will not appear}
@!double_dot: constant eight_bits:=8#40#; {ASCII space will not appear except in strings}
@!join: constant eight_bits:=8#177#; {ASCII delete will not appear}

@ @<Specification of procedures visible from |data_structures|@>=
  procedure store_two_bytes(x:sixteen_bits);
 
@ The following procedure is used to enter a two-byte value into |tok_mem| 
when a replacement text is being generated.

@<Procedures in |data_structures|@>=
procedure @!store_two_bytes(@!x:sixteen_bits)is
  {stores high byte, then low byte}
begin if tok_ptr(z)+2>max_toks then overflow("token");
      end if;
tok_mem(z,tok_ptr(z)):=x/8#400#; {this could be done by a shift command}
tok_mem(z,tok_ptr(z)+1):=x mod 8#400#; {this could be done by a logical and}
tok_ptr(z):=tok_ptr(z)+2;
end store_two_bytes;
 
@* Stacks for output.
Let's make sure that our data structures contain enough information to
produce the entire \ADA\ program as desired, by working next on the
algorithms that actually do produce that program.
 
@ The output process uses a stack to keep track of what is going on at
different ``levels'' as the macros are being expanded.
Entries on this stack have five parts:
 
\yskip\hang |end_field| is the |tok_mem| location where the replacement
text of a particular level will end;
 
\hang |byte_field| is the |tok_mem| location from which the next token
on a particular level will be read;
 
\hang |name_field| points to the name corresponding to a particular level;
 
\hang |repl_field| points to the replacement text currently being read
at a particular level.
 
\hang |mod_field| is the module number, or zero if this is a macro.
 
\yskip\noindent The current values of these five quantities are referred to
quite frequently, so they are stored in a separate place instead of in
the |stack| array. We call the current values |cur_end|, |cur_byte|,
|cur_name|, |cur_repl|, and |cur_mod|.
 
The global variable |stack_ptr| tells how many levels of output are
currently in progress. The end of all output occurs when the stack is
empty, i.e., when |stack_ptr=0|.
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype mod_range is INTEGER range 0..8#27777#;
type @!output_state is record
  @!end_field: sixteen_bits; {ending location of replacement text}
  @!byte_field: sixteen_bits; {present location within replacement text}
  @!name_field: name_pointer; {|byte_start| index for text being output}
  @!repl_field: text_pointer; {|tok_start| index for text being output}
  @!mod_field: mod_range; {module number or zero if not a module}
  end record;
@#
@!cur_state : output_state; {|cur_end|, |cur_byte|, |cur_name|, |cur_repl|}
@!stack : array (1..stack_size) of output_state; 
                                                {info for non-current levels}
@!stack_ptr: INTEGER range 0..stack_size;
                            {first unused location in the output state stack}
@#
@!cur_end:sixteen_bits renames cur_state.end_field; 
                                       {current ending location in |tok_mem|}
@!cur_byte:sixteen_bits renames cur_state.byte_field; 
                                  {location of next output byte in |tok_mem|}
@!cur_name:name_pointer renames cur_state.name_field; 
                                     {pointer to current name being expanded}
@!cur_repl:text_pointer renames cur_state.repl_field; 
                                        {pointer to current replacement text}
@!cur_mod:mod_range renames cur_state.mod_field;
                                       {current module number being expanded}
  
@ It is convenient to keep a global variable |zo| equal to |cur_repl mod zz|.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!zo:z_range; {the segment of |tok_mem| from which output
                             is coming}
 
@ Parameters must also be stacked. They are placed in |tok_mem| just above 
the other replacement texts, and dummy parameter `names' are placed in 
|byte_start| just after the other names. The variables |text_ptr| and 
|tok_ptr(z)| essentially serve as parameter stack pointers during the output 
phase, so there is no need for a separate data structure to handle this 
problem.
 
@ There is an implicit stack corresponding to meta-comments that are output
via \.{@@\{} and \.{@@\}}. But this stack need not be represented in detail,
because we only need to know whether it is empty or not. A global variable
|brace_level| tells how many items would be on this stack if it were present.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!brace_level: eight_bits; 
                          {current depth of $\.{@@\{}\ldots\.{@@\}}$ nesting}

@ To get the output process started, we will perform the following
initialization steps. We may assume that |text_link(0)| is nonzero, since it
points to the \ADA\ text in the first unnamed module that generates code; if 
there are no such modules, there is nothing to output, and an error message 
will have been generated before we do any of the initialization.
 
@<Initialize the output stacks@>=
stack_ptr:=1; brace_level:=0; cur_name:=0; cur_repl:=text_link(0);
zo:=cur_repl mod zz; cur_byte:=tok_start(cur_repl);
cur_end:=tok_start(cur_repl+zz); cur_mod:=0;
 
@ When the replacement text for name |p| is to be inserted into the output,
the following subroutine is called to save the old level of output and get
the new one going.

@<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
procedure @!push_level(@!p:name_pointer)is {suspends the current level}
begin if stack_ptr=stack_size then overflow("stack");
else  stack(stack_ptr):=cur_state; {save |cur_end|, |cur_byte|, etc.}
  incr(stack_ptr);
  cur_name:=p; cur_repl:=equiv(p); zo:=cur_repl mod zz;
  cur_byte:=tok_start(cur_repl); cur_end:=tok_start(cur_repl+zz);
  cur_mod:=0;
  end if;
end push_level;
 
@ When we come to the end of a replacement text, the |pop_level| subroutine
does the right thing: It either moves to the continuation of this replacement
text or returns the state to the most recently stacked level. Part of this
subroutine, which updates the parameter stack, will be given later when we
study the parameter stack in more detail.
 
@<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
procedure @!pop_level is {do this when |cur_byte| reaches |cur_end|}
begin if text_link(cur_repl)=0 then {end of macro expansion}
  if ilk(cur_name)=parametric then
    @<Remove a parameter from the parameter stack@>;
  end if;
elsif text_link(cur_repl)<module_flag then {link to a continuation}
  cur_repl:=text_link(cur_repl); {we will stay on the same level}
  zo:=cur_repl mod zz;
  cur_byte:=tok_start(cur_repl); cur_end:=tok_start(cur_repl+zz);
  @/ return;
  end if;
decr(stack_ptr); {we will go down to the previous level}
if stack_ptr>0 then
  cur_state:=stack(stack_ptr); zo:=cur_repl mod zz;
  end if;
end pop_level;
 
@ The heart of the output procedure is the |get_output| routine, which 
produces the next token of output that is not a reference to a macro. This 
procedure handles all the stacking and unstacking that is necessary. It 
returns the value |module_number| if the next output begins or ends the 
replacement text of some module, in which case |cur_val| is that module's 
number (if beginning) or the negative of that value (if ending). The 
procedure also returns the value |identifier| if the next output is an 
identifier of length two or more, in which case |cur_val| points to that 
identifier name.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!module_number: constant sixteen_bits:=8#201#; {code returned by |get_output| for module numbers}
@!identifier: constant sixteen_bits:=8#202#; {code returned by |get_output| for identifiers}
@#
@!cur_val:INTEGER; {additional information corresponding to output token}
 
@ If |get_output| finds that no more output remains, it returns the value 
zero.
 
@<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
function @!get_output return sixteen_bits is
                                   {returns next token after macro expansion}
@!a:sixteen_bits; {value of current byte}
@!b:eight_bits; {byte being copied}
@!bal:sixteen_bits; {excess of \.( versus \.) while copying a parameter}
@!k:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
@!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
begin <<restart>> if stack_ptr=0 then return 0; end if;
if cur_byte=cur_end then
  cur_val:=-cur_mod; pop_level;
  if cur_val=0 then goto restart; end if;
  return module_number;
  end if;
a:=tok_mem(zo,cur_byte); incr(cur_byte);
if a<8#200# then {one-byte token}
  if a=param then
      @<Start scanning current macro parameter, |goto restart|@>;
  else return a;
  end if;
end if;
a:=(a-8#200#)*8#400#+tok_mem(zo,cur_byte); incr(cur_byte);
if a<8#24000# then {|8#24000#=(8#250#-8#200#)*8#400#|}
  @<Expand macro |a| and |return@;|, or |goto restart@;| if no output found@>;
end if;
if a<8#50000# then {|8#50000#=(8#320#-8#200#)*8#400#|}
  @<Expand module |a-8#24000#|, |goto restart|@>;
end if;
cur_val:=a-8#50000#; cur_mod:=cur_val; return module_number;
end get_output;
 
@ The user may have forgotten to give any \ADA\ text for a module name,
or the \ADA\ text may have been associated with a different name by mistake.
 
@<Expand module |a-...@>=
a:=a-8#24000#;
if equiv(a)/=0 then push_level(a);
elsif a/=0 then
  print_nl("! Not present: <"); print_id(a); print(">"); error;
@.Not present: <section name>@>
end if;
goto restart@;
 
@ @<Expand macro ...@>=
case ilk(a) is
when normal => cur_val:=a; return identifier;
when simple => push_level(a); goto restart;
when parametric => @<Put a parameter on the parameter stack,
  or |goto restart| if error occurs@>;
  push_level(a); goto restart;
when others => confusion("output");
end case;@/
return a@;
 
@ We come now to the interesting part, the job of putting a parameter on
the parameter stack. First we pop the stack if necessary until getting to
a level that hasn't ended. Then the next character must be a `\.(';
and since parentheses are balanced on each level, the entire parameter must
be present, so we can copy it without difficulty.
 
@<Put a parameter...@>=
while (cur_byte=cur_end)and(stack_ptr>0) loop pop_level; end loop;
if (stack_ptr=0)or(tok_mem(zo,cur_byte)/=@'(') then
  print_nl("! No parameter given for "); print_id(a); error;
@.No parameter given for macro@>
  goto restart;
  end if;
@<Copy the parameter into |tok_mem|@>;
equiv(name_ptr):=text_ptr; ilk(name_ptr):=simple; w:=name_ptr mod ww;
k:=byte_ptr(w);
if name_ptr>max_names-ww then overflow("name"); end if;
byte_start(name_ptr+ww):=k; incr(name_ptr);
if text_ptr>max_texts-zz then overflow("text"); end if;
text_link(text_ptr):=0; tok_start(text_ptr+zz):=tok_ptr(z);
incr(text_ptr);
z:=text_ptr mod zz@;
 
@ The |pop_level| routine undoes the effect of parameter-pushing when
a parameter macro is finished:
 
@<Remove a parameter...@>=
decr(name_ptr); decr(text_ptr);
z:=text_ptr mod zz;
stat if tok_ptr(z)>max_tok_ptr(z) then max_tok_ptr(z):=tok_ptr(z); end if;
tats@; {the maximum value of |tok_ptr| occurs just before parameter popping}
tok_ptr(z):=tok_start(text_ptr)@;
 
@ When a parameter occurs in a replacement text, we treat it as a simple
macro in position (|name_ptr-1|):
 
@<Start scanning...@>=
push_level(name_ptr-1); goto restart@;
 
@ Similarly, a |param| token encountered as we copy a parameter is converted
into a simple macro call for |name_ptr-1|. Some care is needed to handle 
cases like \\{macro}|(#; print("#)"))|; the \.{\#} token will have been 
changed to |param| outside of strings, but we still must distinguish `real' 
parentheses from those in strings.
 
@d app_repl(#)==if tok_ptr(z)=max_toks then overflow("token"); end if;
  tok_mem(z,tok_ptr(z)):=#; incr(tok_ptr(z))@;
 
@<Copy the parameter...@>=
bal:=1; incr(cur_byte); {skip the opening `\.('}
loop  b:=tok_mem(zo,cur_byte); incr(cur_byte);
  if b=param then store_two_bytes(name_ptr+8#77777#);
  else  if b>=8#200# then
      app_repl(b);
      b:=tok_mem(zo,cur_byte); incr(cur_byte);
    else   case b is
      when @'(' => incr(bal);
      when @')' => decr(bal);
        exit when bal=0;
      when character_tok ! ascii_tok =>
        app_repl(b);
        b:=tok_mem(zo,cur_byte); incr(cur_byte);
      when @'"' => repeat app_repl(b);
        b:=tok_mem(zo,cur_byte); incr(cur_byte);
        if b=@'"' and tok_mem(zo,cur_byte)=@'"' then
          app_repl(@'"'); app_repl(@'"');
          b:=tok_mem(zo,cur_byte+1);
          cur_byte:=cur_byte+2;
        end if;
	until(b=@'"'); {copy string, don't change |bal|}
      when others => null;
      end case;
    end if;
    app_repl(b);
    end if;
  end loop@;


@* Producing the output.
The |get_output| routine above handles most of the complexity of output
generation, but there are two further considerations that have a nontrivial
effect on \.{ATANGLE}'s algorithms.
 
First, we want to make sure that the output is broken into lines not
exceeding |line_length| characters per line, where these breaks occur at
valid places (e.g., not in the middle of a string or a constant or an
identifier, not between `\./' and `\.=', not at a `\.{@@\&}' position
where quantities are being joined together). Therefore we assemble the
output into a buffer before deciding where the line breaks will appear.
However, we make very little attempt to make ``logical'' line breaks that
would enhance the readability of the output; people are supposed to read
the input of \.{ATANGLE} or the \TeX ed output of \.{AWEAVE}, but not the
tangled-up output. The only concession to readability is that a break after
a semicolon will be made if possible, since commonly used ``pretty
printing'' routines give better results in such cases.
 
The following solution to these problems has been adopted: An array
|out_buf| contains characters that have been generated but not yet output,
and there are three pointers into this array. One of these, |out_ptr|, is
the number of characters currently in the buffer, and we will have
|1<=out_ptr<=line_length| most of the time. The second is |break_ptr|,
which is the largest value |<=out_ptr| such that we are definitely entitled
to end a line by outputting the characters |out_buf(1..(break_ptr-1))|;
we will always have |break_ptr<=line_length|. Finally, |semi_ptr| is either
zero or the largest known value of a legal break after a semicolon
on the current line; we will always have |semi_ptr<=break_ptr|.
 
@<Types...@>=
subtype out_buffer_index is INTEGER range 0..out_buf_size;
@!out_buf: buffer_type(out_buffer_index); {assembled characters}
@!out_ptr: out_buffer_index; {first available place in |out_buf|}
@!break_ptr: out_buffer_index; {last breaking place in |out_buf|}
@!semi_ptr: out_buffer_index; {last semicolon breaking place in |out_buf|}
 
@ Besides having those three pointers,
the output process is in one of several states:
 
\yskip\hang |num_or_id| means that the last item in the buffer is a number or
identifier, hence a blank space or line break must be inserted if the next
item is also a number or identifier.
 
\yskip\hang |unbreakable| means that the last item in the buffer was followed
by the \.{@@\&} operation that inhibits spaces between it and the next item.
 
\yskip\hang |misc| means none of the above.
 
\yskip\noindent
In all states the last item in the buffer lies between |break_ptr| and 
|out_ptr-1|, inclusive.
 
Beside the states there is a boolean variable, called |comment_output|,
which is set true, if the material to be output is part of the meta-comments
between `\.{@@\{}' and `\.{@@\}}' and therefore has to be preceded by 
`\.{--}'.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!misc: constant eight_bits:=0; {state associated with special characters}
@!num_or_id: constant eight_bits:=1; {state associated with numbers and identifiers}
@!unbreakable:constant eight_bits:=2; {state associated with \.{@@\&}}
@#
@!out_state:eight_bits; {current status of partial output}
@!comment_output:BOOLEAN; {outputting meta-comment?}
  
@ During the output process, |line| will equal the number of the next line
to be output.
 
@<Initialize the output buffer@>=
out_state:=misc; out_ptr:=0; break_ptr:=0; semi_ptr:=0; out_buf(0):=0; 
line:=1; comment_output:=FALSE;
 
@ Here is a routine that is invoked when |out_ptr>line_length|
or when it is time to flush out the final line. The |flush_buffer| procedure
often writes out the line up to the current |break_ptr| position, then moves the
remaining information to the front of |out_buf|. However, it prefers to
write only up to |semi_ptr|, if the residual line won't be too long.
 
@d check_break==if out_ptr>line_length then flush_buffer; end if
 
@<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
procedure @!flush_buffer is {writes one line to output file}
@!b:out_buffer_index := break_ptr; {value of |break_ptr| upon entry}
begin
if comment_output then TEXT_IO.PUT(ada_file,"--"); end if;
if (semi_ptr/=0)and(out_ptr-semi_ptr<=line_length) then break_ptr:=semi_ptr;
end if;
for k in 1..break_ptr loop TEXT_IO.PUT(ada_file,xchr(out_buf(k-1)));
end loop;
new_ln(ada_file); incr(line); incr(f_line);
if line mod 100 = 0 then
  print(".");
  if line mod 500 = 0 then print_int(line,1);
  update_terminal; {progress report}
  end if;
end if;
if break_ptr<out_ptr then
  if out_buf(break_ptr)=@' ' then
    incr(break_ptr); {drop space at break}
    if break_ptr>b then b:=break_ptr;
    end if;
  end if;
  out_buf(0..out_ptr-break_ptr-1):=out_buf(break_ptr..out_ptr-1);
end if;
out_ptr:=out_ptr-break_ptr; break_ptr:=b-break_ptr; semi_ptr:=0;
if out_ptr>line_length then
  err_print("! Long line must be truncated"); @/ out_ptr:=line_length;
@.Long line must be truncated@>
end if;
end flush_buffer;
 
@ @<Empty the last line from the buffer@>=
break_ptr:=out_ptr; semi_ptr:=0; flush_buffer;
if brace_level/=0 then new_ln;
  print("! Program ended at brace level "); print_int(brace_level,1); error;
end if;
@.Program ended at brace level n@>
 
@ Another simple and useful routine appends the decimal equivalent of
a nonnegative integer to the output buffer.
 
@d app(#)==out_buf(out_ptr):=#; incr(out_ptr) {append a single character}
 
@<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
procedure @!send_val(@!v:INTEGER) is {puts |v| into buffer, assumes |v>=0|}
@!k:out_buffer_index := out_buf_size; {index into |out_buf|}
@!u:INTEGER := v;
begin {first we put the digits at the very end of |out_buf|}
repeat out_buf(k):=u mod 10; u:=u/10; decr(k);
until(u=0);
repeat incr(k); app(out_buf(k)+@'0');
until(k=out_buf_size); {then we append them, most significant first}
end send_val;
 
@ The output states are kept up to date by the |send_out| procedure, which
has two parameters: |t| tells the type of information being sent and
|v| contains the information proper. Some information may also be passed
in the array |out_contrib|.
 
\yskip\hang If |t=misc| then |v| is a character to be output.
 
\hang If |t=str| then |v| is the length of a string or something like 
`\.{/=}' in |out_contrib|.
 
\hang If |t=ident| then |v| is the length of an identifier in |out_contrib|.
 
\hang If |t=frac| then |v| is the length of a fraction and/or exponent in
|out_contrib|.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!str: constant eight_bits:=1; {|send_out| code for a string}
@!ident: constant eight_bits:=2; {|send_out| code for an identifier}
@!frac: constant eight_bits:=3; {|send_out| code for a fraction}
@#
@!out_contrib:buffer_type(1..line_length); {a contribution to |out_buf|}
 
@ A slightly subtle point in the following code is that the user may ask
for a |join| operation (i.e., \.{@@\&}) following whatever is being sent
out.  We will see later that |join| is implemented in part by calling
|send_out(frac,0)|.
 
@<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
procedure @!send_out(@!t:eight_bits; @!v:sixteen_bits) is
  {outputs |v| of type |t|}
begin @<Get the buffer ready for appending the new information@>;
if t/=misc then for k in 1..v loop app(out_contrib(k)); end loop;
else app(v);
end if;
check_break;
if (t=misc)and(v=@';') then
  semi_ptr:=out_ptr; break_ptr:=out_ptr;
  end if;
if t>=ident then out_state:=num_or_id; {|t=ident| or |frac|}
else out_state:=misc; {|t=str| or |misc|}
end if;
end send_out;
 
@ @<Get the buffer ready...@>=
<<restart>> case out_state is
when num_or_id => if t/=frac then
  break_ptr:=out_ptr;
  if t=ident then app(@' '); end if;
  end if;
when misc => if t/=frac then break_ptr:=out_ptr; end if;
when others => null; {this is for |unbreakable| state}
end case@;
 
@* The big output switch.
To complete the output process, we need a routine that takes the results
of |get_output| and feeds them to |send_out| or |send_val|.
This procedure `|send_the_output|' will be invoked just once, as follows:
 
@<Phase II: Output the contents of the compressed tables@>=
if text_link(0)=0 then
  print_nl("! No output was specified."); mark_harmless;
@.No output was specified@>
else  print_nl("Writing the output file"); update_terminal;@/
  @<Initialize the output stacks@>@;
  @<Initialize the output buffer@>@;
  send_the_output;@/
  @<Empty the last line...@>@;
  print_nl("Done.");
end if@;
 
@ A many-way switch is used to send the output:
 
@<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
procedure @!send_the_output is
  @!cur_char:eight_bits; {the latest character received}
  @!k:INTEGER range 0..line_length; {index into |out_contrib|}
  @!j:byte_index; {index into |byte_mem|}
  @!w:w_range; {segment of |byte_mem|}
begin while stack_ptr>0 loop
  cur_char:=get_output;
  <<reswitch>> case cur_char is
  when 0 => @+null; {this case might arise if output ends unexpectedly}
  @t\4@>@<Cases related to identifiers@>@;
  @t\4@>@<Cases related to constants, possibly leading to
    |get_fraction| or |reswitch|@>@;
  @t\4@>@<Cases like \.{/=} and \.{:=}@>@;
  when @'"' => @+@<Send a string, |goto reswitch|@>;
  when @<Other printable characters@> => @+send_out(misc,cur_char);@/
  @t\4@>@<Cases involving \.{@@\{} and \.{@@\}}@>@;
  when join => @+send_out(frac,0); out_state:=unbreakable;
  when verbatim => @+@<Send verbatim string@>;
  when output_tok => @+@<Get the |file_name| and redirect further output@>;
  when force_line => @+@<Force a line break@>;
  when others => new_ln; print("! Can't output ASCII code ");
                 print_int(cur_char,1); error;
@.Can't output ASCII code n@>
  end case;
  goto continue;
  <<get_fraction>> @<Special code to finish real constants@>;
  <<continue>> null;
  end loop;
end send_the_output;
 
@ @<Cases like \.{/=}...@>=
when and_sign => @+out_contrib(1..3):=(@'A',@'N',@'D');
@^uppercase@>
  send_out(ident,3);
when not_sign => @+out_contrib(1..3):=(@'N',@'O',@'T');
  send_out(ident,3);
when set_element_sign => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'I',@'N');
  send_out(ident,2);
when or_sign => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'O',@'R'); send_out(ident,2);
when left_arrow => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@':',@'='); send_out(str,2);
when not_equal => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'/',@'='); send_out(str,2);
when less_or_equal => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'<',@'='); send_out(str,2);
when greater_or_equal => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'>',@'=');
  send_out(str,2);
when equivalence_sign => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'=',@'=');
  send_out(str,2);
when double_dot => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'.',@'.'); send_out(str,2);
when right_arrow => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'=',@'>'); send_out(str,2);
when box_sign => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'<',@'>'); send_out(str,2);
when left_label_bracket => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'<',@'<');
  send_out(str,2);
when right_label_bracket => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'>',@'>');
  send_out(str,2);
when double_star => @+out_contrib(1..2):=(@'*',@'*'); send_out(str,2);
when character_tok => @+out_contrib(1..3):=(@''',get_output,@''');
                      send_out(str,3);
when ascii_tok => if out_state=num_or_id then send_out(misc,@' '); end if;
                  send_val(get_output); out_state:=num_or_id;

@ Please don't ask how all of the following characters can actually get
through \.{ATANGLE} outside of strings. It seems that |@'{'|
cannot actually occur at this point of the program, but it has
been included just in case \.{ATANGLE} changes.
 
@<Other printable characters@>=
     @'!' ! @'#' ! @'$' ! @'%' ! @'&' ! @''' ! @'(' ! @')' ! @'*' ! @',' !
     @'/' ! @':' ! @';' ! @'<' ! @'=' ! @'>' ! @'?' ! @'@@'! @'[' ! @'\' !
     @']' ! @'^' ! @'_' ! @'`' ! @'{' ! @'|' ! @'+' ! @'-'

@ Single-character identifiers represent themselves, while longer ones
appear in |byte_mem|. All must be converted to uppercase,
with underlines removed. Extremely long identifiers must be chopped.
 
@<Cases related to identifiers@>=
when @'A'..@'Z' => @+out_contrib(1):=cur_char; send_out(ident,1);
when @'a'..@'z' => @+out_contrib(1):=cur_char-8#40#; send_out(ident,1);
when identifier => @+k:=0; j:=byte_start(cur_val); w:=cur_val mod ww;
  while (k<max_id_length)and(j<byte_start(cur_val+ww)) loop
    incr(k); out_contrib(k):=byte_mem(w,j); incr(j);
    if out_contrib(k)>=@'a' then out_contrib(k):=out_contrib(k)-8#40#;
    end if;
  end loop;
  send_out(ident,k);
 
@ After sending a string, we need to look ahead at the next character, in order
to see if there were two consecutive single-quote marks. Afterwards we go to
|reswitch| to process the next character.
 
@<Send a string...@>=
k:=1; out_contrib(1):=@'"';
repeat if k<line_length then incr(k); end if;
out_contrib(k):=get_output;
until((out_contrib(k)=@'"')or(stack_ptr=0));
if k=line_length then err_print("! String too long");
@.String too long@>
end if;
send_out(str,k); cur_char:=get_output;
if cur_char=@'"' then out_state:=unbreakable; end if;
goto reswitch@;
 
@ Sending a verbatim string is similar, but we don't have to look ahead.
 
@<Send verbatim string@>=
k:=0;
repeat if k<line_length then incr(k); end if;
out_contrib(k):=get_output;
until((out_contrib(k)=verbatim)or(stack_ptr=0));
if k=line_length then err_print("! Verbatim string too long");
@.Verbatim string too long@>
end if;
send_out(str,k-1)@;

@ Getting the new output file name is similar to sending a verbatim string;
if there is a legal name, the file will be created and the variables
|file_name| and |fn_length| will be set accordingly and |f_line| is set
to~1.

@<Types...@>=
@!file_name:STRING(1..256);
@!fn_length:INTEGER range 1..256;
@!f_line:INTEGER;

@ Before we redirect output we will empty the output buffer.

@<Get the |file_name| and...@>=
@<Force a line break@>;
k:=0;
loop
  cur_char:=get_output;
  exit when (cur_char=output_tok)or(stack_ptr=0);@/
  incr(k);
  file_name(k):=xchr(cur_char);
end loop;
if k>0 then
  TEXT_IO.CLOSE(ada_file);
  fn_length:=k;
  if not create_ada_file(file_name(1..k)) then
    fatal_error("! Could not open file `"&file_name(1..k)&"'.");
@.Could not open file `x'@>
  end if;
  f_line:=1;
else
  err_print("! File name should have length > 0");
@.File name should have length > 0@>
end if@;
 
@ In the cases related to numeric literals there is some care needed,
  because of the ``based literal'', which \ADA\ supports; a global
  variable |scanning_based_number| tells whether there is more to do.

@<Types...@>=
@!scanning_based_number:BOOLEAN:=FALSE;
 
@ @<Cases related to constants...@>=
when @'0'..@'9' => scanning_based_number:=FALSE;
  k:=0;
  loop if cur_char/=@'_' then
      incr(k); out_contrib(k):=cur_char; cur_char:=get_output;
      if cur_char=@'#' then
        scanning_based_number:= not scanning_based_number;
      else
        exit when  ((not scanning_based_number) and
                    (cur_char not in @'0'..@'9') and (cur_char/=@'_'));
      end if;
    else cur_char:=get_output;
    end if;
  end loop;
  send_out(ident,k);
  k:=0;
  if cur_char=@'e' then cur_char:=@'E';
@^uppercase@>
  end if;
  if cur_char=@'E' then goto get_fraction;
  else goto reswitch;
  end if;
when @'.' =>  k:=1; out_contrib(1):=@'.'; cur_char:=get_output;
  if cur_char=@'.' then
    out_contrib(2):=@'.'; send_out(str,2);
  elsif cur_char in @'0'..@'9' then goto get_fraction;
  else  send_out(misc,@'.'); goto reswitch;
  end if;
 
@ The following code appears at label `|get_fraction|', when we want to
scan to the end of a real constant. The first |k| characters of a fraction
have already been placed in |out_contrib|, and |cur_char| is the next character.
 
@<Special code...@>=
repeat if k<line_length then incr(k); end if;
out_contrib(k):=cur_char; cur_char:=get_output;
if (out_contrib(k)=@'E')and((cur_char=@'+')or(cur_char=@'-')) then
@^uppercase@>
  if k<line_length then incr(k); end if;
  out_contrib(k):=cur_char; cur_char:=get_output;
elsif cur_char=@'e' then cur_char:=@'E';
end if;
until((cur_char/=@'E')and(cur_char not in @'0'..@'9'));
if k=line_length then err_print("! Fraction too long"); end if;
@.Fraction too long@>
send_out(frac,k); goto reswitch@;
 
@ Here the variable |comment_output| is set corresponding to the value of
|brace_level|; further after each comment a line break is inserted.

@<Cases involving \.{@@\{} and \.{@@\}}@>=
when begin_comment => @<Force a line break@>;
                      incr(brace_level);
		      comment_output:=TRUE;
when end_comment => if brace_level>0 then
    decr(brace_level);
    if brace_level=0 then @<Force a line break@>; comment_output:=FALSE;
    end if;
  else err_print("! Extra @@}");
@.Extra \AT!\}@>
  end if;
when module_number => semi_ptr:=0;
  out_contrib(1..2):=(@'-',@'-'); send_out(str,2);
  while cur_char=module_number loop
    out_state:=unbreakable;
    send_out(misc,@'{');
    out_state:=unbreakable;
    if cur_val<0 then
      send_out(misc,@':'); out_state:=unbreakable; send_val(-cur_val);
    else  send_val(cur_val); out_state:=unbreakable; send_out(misc,@':');
    end if;
    out_state:=unbreakable; send_out(misc,@'}');
    cur_char:=get_output;
  end loop;
  @<Force a line break@>;
  goto reswitch;
 
@ @<Force a line break@>=
send_out(str,0); {normalize the buffer}
while out_ptr>0 loop
  if out_ptr<=line_length then break_ptr:=out_ptr; end if;
  flush_buffer;
  end loop;
out_state:=misc@;
 
@ @<Procedures in |output_phase|@>=
procedure @!phase_ii is
begin
  @<Phase II...@>;
end phase_ii;


@* Introduction to the input phase.
We have now seen that \.{ATANGLE} will be able to output the full
\ADA\ program, if we can only get that program into the byte memory in
the proper format. The input process is something like the output process
in reverse, since we compress the text as we read it in and we expand it
as we write it out.
 
There are three main input routines. The most interesting is the one that 
gets the next token of an \ADA\ text; the other two are used to scan rapidly
past \TeX\ text in the \.{AWEB} source code. One of the latter routines will
jump to the next token that starts with `\.{@@}', and the other skips to the 
end of an \ADA\ comment.
 
@ But first we need to consider the low-level routine |get_line|
that takes care of merging |change_file| into |web_file|. The |get_line|
procedure also updates the line numbers for error messages.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!line:INTEGER; {the number of the current line in the current file}
@!other_line:INTEGER; {the number of the current line in the input file that
  is not currently being read}
@!temp_line:INTEGER; {used when interchanging |line| with |other_line|}
@!limit:buffer_index; {the last character position occupied in the buffer}
@!loc:buffer_index; {the next character position to be read from the buffer}
@!input_has_ended: BOOLEAN; {if |TRUE|, there is no more input}
@!changing: BOOLEAN; {if |TRUE|, the current line is from |change_file|}
 
@ As we change |changing| from |TRUE| to |FALSE| and back again, we must
remember to swap the values of |line| and |other_line| so that the 
|err_print| routine will be sure to report the correct line number.
 
@d change_changing==
  changing := not changing;
  temp_line:=other_line; other_line:=line; line:=temp_line@;
    {|line @t$\null\BA\null$@> other_line|}
 
@ When |changing| is |FALSE|, the next line of |change_file| is kept in
|change_buffer(0..change_limit)|, for purposes of comparison with the next
line of |web_file|. After the change file has been completely input, we
set |change_limit:=0|, so that no further matches will be made.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!change_buffer:buffer_type(buffer_index);
@!change_limit:buffer_index; {the last position occupied in |change_buffer|}
 
@ Here's a simple function that checks if the two buffers are different.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
function @!lines_dont_match return BOOLEAN is
begin 
if change_limit/=limit then return TRUE;
end if;
if limit>0 and then
  change_buffer(0..limit-1)/=buffer(0..limit-1) then return TRUE;
else return FALSE;
end if;
end lines_dont_match;
 
@ Procedure |prime_the_change_buffer| sets |change_buffer| in preparation
for the next matching operation. Since blank lines in the change file are
not used for matching, we have |(change_limit=0)and not changing| if and
only if the change file is exhausted. This procedure is called only
when |changing| is true; hence error messages will be reported correctly.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!prime_the_change_buffer is
begin change_limit:=0; {this value will be used if the change file ends}
@<Skip over comment lines in the change file; |return@;| if end of file@>;
@<Skip to the next nonblank line; |return@;| if end of file@>;
@<Move |buffer| and |limit| to |change_buffer| and |change_limit|@>;
end prime_the_change_buffer;
 
@ While looking for a line that begins with \.{@@x} in the change file,
we allow lines that begin with \.{@@}, as long as they don't begin with
\.{@@y} or \.{@@z} (which would probably indicate that the change file is
fouled up).
 
@<Skip over comment lines in the change file...@>=
loop  incr(line);
  if not input_ln(change_file) then return; end if;
  if limit<2 then goto continue; end if;
  if buffer(0)/=@'@@' then goto continue; end if;
  if buffer(1) in @'X'..@'Z' then
    buffer(1):=buffer(1)+@'z'-@'Z'; {lowercasify}
  end if;
  exit when buffer(1)=@'x';
  if buffer(1) in @'y'..@'z' then
    loc:=2; err_print("! Where is the matching @@x?");
@.Where is the match...@>
    end if;
<<continue>> null; 
end loop@;
 
@ Here we are looking at lines following the \.{@@x}.
 
@<Skip to the next nonblank line...@>=
repeat incr(line);
  if not input_ln(change_file) then
    err_print("! Change file ended after @@x");@/
@.Change file ended...@>
    return;
    end if;
until(limit>0)@;
   
@ @<Move |buffer| and |limit| to |change_buffer| and |change_limit|@>=
change_limit:=limit;
if limit>0 then change_buffer(0..limit-1):=buffer(0..limit-1);
end if@;
 
@ The following procedure is used to see if the next change entry should
go into effect; it is called only when |changing| is false.
The idea is to test whether or not the current
contents of |buffer| matches the current contents of |change_buffer|.
If not, there's nothing more to do; but if so, a change is called for:
All of the text down to the \.{@@y} is supposed to match. An error
message is issued if any discrepancy is found. Then the procedure
prepares to read the next line from |change_file|.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!check_change is {switches to |change_file| if the buffers match}
@!n:INTEGER:=0; {the number of discrepancies found}
begin if lines_dont_match then return; end if;
loop  change_changing; {now it's |TRUE|}
  incr(line);
  if not input_ln(change_file) then
    err_print("! Change file ended before @@y"); @/
@.Change file ended...@>
    change_limit:=0;  change_changing; {|FALSE| again}
    return;
    end if;
  @<If the current line starts with \.{@@y},
    report any discrepancies and |return@;|@>;
  @<Move |buffer| and |limit|...@>;
  change_changing; {now it's |FALSE|}
  incr(line);
  if not input_ln(web_file) then
    err_print("! AWEB file ended during a change"); @/
@.AWEB file ended...@>
    input_has_ended:=TRUE; return;
    end if;
  if lines_dont_match then incr(n); end if;
  end loop;
end check_change;
 
@ @<If the current line starts with \.{@@y}...@>=
if (limit>1) and then buffer(0)=@'@@' then
  if buffer(1) in @'X'..@'Z' then
    buffer(1):=buffer(1)+@'z'-@'Z'; {lowercasify}
  end if;
  if (buffer(1)=@'x')or(buffer(1)=@'z') then
    loc:=2; err_print("! Where is the matching @@y?");
@.Where is the match...@>
  elsif buffer(1)=@'y' then
    if n>0 then
      loc:=2; new_ln;
      print("! Hmm... ");
      print_int(n,1);
      print(" of the preceding lines failed to match");
@.Hmm... n of the preceding...@>
      error;
    end if;
    return;
  end if;
end if@;
 
@ @<Initialize the input system@>=
line:=0; other_line:=0;@/
changing:=TRUE; prime_the_change_buffer; change_changing;@/
limit:=0; loc:=1; buffer(0):=@' '; input_has_ended:=FALSE@;
 
@ The |get_line| procedure is called when |loc>limit|; it puts the next
line of merged input into the buffer and updates the other variables
appropriately. A space is placed at the right end of the line.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!get_line is {inputs the next line}
begin <<restart>> if changing then
  @<Read from |change_file| and maybe turn off |changing|@>;
end if;
if not changing then
  @<Read from |web_file| and maybe turn on |changing|@>;
  if changing then goto restart; end if;
end if;
loc:=0; buffer(limit):=@' ';
end get_line;
 
@ @<Read from |web_file|...@>=
incr(line);
if not input_ln(web_file) then input_has_ended:=TRUE;
elsif (limit=change_limit) and then
      ((buffer(0)=change_buffer(0)) and then
      (change_limit>0)) then check_change;
end if@;
 
@ @<Read from |change_file|...@>=
incr(line);
if not input_ln(change_file) then
  err_print("! Change file ended without @@z"); @/
@.Change file ended...@>
  buffer(0..1):=(@'@@',@'z'); limit:=2;
end if;
if (limit>1) and then (buffer(0)=@'@@') then {check if the change has ended}
  if buffer(1) in @'X'..@'Z' then
    buffer(1):=buffer(1)+@'z'-@'Z'; {lowercasify}
  end if;
  if buffer(1) in @'x'..@'y' then
    loc:=2; err_print("! Where is the matching @@z?");
@.Where is the match...@>
  elsif buffer(1)=@'z' then
    prime_the_change_buffer; change_changing;
  end if;
end if@;

 
@ At the end of the program, we will tell the user if the change file
had a line that didn't match any relevant line in |web_file|.
 
@<Check that all changes have been read@>=
if change_limit/=0 then {|changing| is false}
  buffer(0..change_limit):=change_buffer(0..change_limit);
  limit:=change_limit; changing:=TRUE; line:=other_line; loc:=change_limit;
  err_print("! Change file entry did not match");
@.Change file entry did not match@>
end if@;
 
@ Important milestones are reached during the input phase when certain
control codes are sensed.
 
Control codes in \.{AWEB} begin with `\.{@@}', and the next character
identifies the code. Some of these are of interest only to \.{AWEAVE},
so \.{ATANGLE} ignores them; the others are converted by \.{ATANGLE} into
internal code numbers by the |control_code| function below. The ordering
of these internal code numbers has been chosen to simplify the program logic;
larger numbers are given to the control codes that denote more significant
milestones.

@<Types...@>=
@!ignore: constant eight_bits:=0; {control code of no interest to \.{ATANGLE}}
@!control_text: constant eight_bits:=8#203#; {control code for `\.{@@t}', `\.{@@\^}', etc.}
@!format:constant eight_bits:=8#204#; {control code for `\.{@@f}'}
@!definition:constant eight_bits:=8#205#; {control code for `\.{@@d}'}
@!begin_ada:constant eight_bits:=8#206#; {control code for `\.{@@a}'}
@!module_name:constant eight_bits:=8#207#; {control code for `\.{@@<}'}
@!new_module:constant eight_bits:=8#210#; {control code for `\.{@@\ }' and `\.{@@*}'}
 
@ @<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
function @!control_code(@!c:ASCII_code) return eight_bits is
                                                   {convert |c| after \.{@@}}
begin case c is
when @'@@'           => @+return @'@@'; {`quoted' at sign}
when @'''            => @+return ascii_tok; {precedes ASCII code constant}
when @'~'            => @+return output_tok; {precedes output file-name}
when @' ' ! tab_mark => @+return new_module; {beginning of a new module}
when @'*'            => @+print("*");
                        print_int(module_count+1,1);
                        update_terminal; {print a progress report}
                        return new_module; {beginning of a new module}
when @'D' ! @'d'     => @+return definition; {macro definition}
when @'F' ! @'f'     => @+return format; {format definition}
when @'{'            => @+return begin_comment; {begin-comment delimiter}
when @'}'            => @+return end_comment; {end-comment delimiter}
when @'A' ! @'a'     => @+return begin_ada; {\ADA\ text in unnamed module}
when @'T' ! @'t' ! @'^' ! @'i' ! @'I' ! @'b' ! @'B' ! @'r' ! @'R' !
     @'p' ! @'P' ! @'s' ! @'S' !
     @'.' ! @':'     => @+return control_text; {control text to be ignored}
when @'&'            => @+return join; {concatenate two tokens}
when @'<'            => @+return module_name; {beginning of a module name}
when @'='            => @+return verbatim; {beginning of \ADA\ verbatim mode}
when @'\'            => @+return force_line; {force a new line in \ADA\ output}
when others          => @+return ignore; {ignore all other cases}
end case;
end control_code;
 
@ The |skip_ahead| procedure reads through the input at fairly high speed
until finding the next non-ignorable control code, which it returns.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
function @!skip_ahead return eight_bits is {skip to next control code}
@!c:eight_bits; {control code found}
begin loop if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      return new_module;
      end if;
    end if;
  buffer(limit+1):=@'@@';
  while buffer(loc)/=@'@@' loop incr(loc); end loop;
  if loc<=limit then
    loc:=loc+2; c:=control_code(buffer(loc-1));
    if (c/=ignore)or(buffer(loc-1)=@'>') then return c; 
    end if;
  end if;
end loop;
end skip_ahead;
 
@ The |skip_comment| procedure reads through the input at somewhat high speed
until finding the first unmatched right brace or until coming to the end
of the file. It ignores characters following `\.\\' characters, since all
braces that aren't nested are supposed to be hidden in that way. For
example, consider the process of skipping the first comment below,
where the string containing the right brace has been typed as \.{`\\.\\\}'}
in the \.{AWEB} file.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!skip_comment is {skips to next unmatched `\.\}'}
@!bal:eight_bits:=0; {excess of left braces}
@!c:ASCII_code; {current character}
begin 
loop  if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      err_print("! Input ended in mid-comment"); @/
@.Input ended in mid-comment@>
      return;
    end if;
  end if;
  c:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);@/
  @<Do special things when |c="@@", "\", "{", "}"|; |return@;| at end@>;
  end loop;
end skip_comment;
 
@ @<Do special things when |c="@@"...@>=
if c=@'@@' then
  c:=buffer(loc);
  if (c/=@' ')and(c/=tab_mark)and(c/=@'*')and(c/=@'z')and(c/=@'Z') then
     incr(loc);
  else  err_print("! Section ended in mid-comment"); @/
@.Section ended in mid-comment@>
    decr(loc); return;
  end if;
elsif (c=@'\')and(buffer(loc)/=@'@@') then incr(loc);
elsif c=@'{' then incr(bal);
elsif c=@'}' then
  if bal=0 then return; end if;
  decr(bal);
end if@;
 
@* Inputting the next token.
As stated above, \.{ATANGLE}'s most interesting input procedure is the
|get_next| routine that inputs the next token. However, the procedure
isn't especially difficult.
 
In most cases the tokens output by |get_next| have the form used in
replacement texts, except that two-byte tokens are not produced.
An identifier that isn't one letter long is represented by the
output `|identifier|', and in such a case the global variables
|id_first| and |id_loc| will have been set to the appropriate values
needed by the |id_lookup| procedure. 
Control codes produce the corresponding output of the |control_code|
function above; and if that code is |module_name|, the value of |cur_module|
will point to the |byte_start| entry for that module name.
 
Another global variable, |scanning_based_number|, is |TRUE| during the time
that letters should be treated as if they were digits; |scanning_character|
is set |TRUE| if the input \.'$x$\.', where $x$ is a character, or the
ASCII code controlcode `\.{@@'} is encoutered.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!cur_module: name_pointer; {name of module just scanned}
@!scanning_character: BOOLEAN:=FALSE; {are we scanning a character literal?}
 
@ At the top level, |get_next| is a multi-way switch based on the next
character in the input buffer. A |new_module| code is inserted at the
very end of the input file.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
function @!get_next return eight_bits is {produces the next input token}
@!c:eight_bits; {the current character}
@!d:eight_bits; {the next character}
@!k:long_name_index; {index into |mod_text|}
begin <<restart>> if loc>limit then
  get_line;
  if input_has_ended then
    return new_module; 
  elsif scanning_based_number then
    err_print("! Improper based number, # sign missing"); @/
@.Improper based number...@>
    scanning_based_number:=FALSE;
  end if;
end if;
c:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
if scanning_based_number then
  if c=@'#' then scanning_based_number:=FALSE; end if;
  return c;
elsif scanning_character then
  if c=@'@@' then
    if buffer(loc)=@'@@' then
      incr(loc);
    else err_print("! You should double @@ signs in character literals");
@.You should double \AT! signs@>
    end if;
  end if;
  incr(loc); scanning_character:=FALSE; return c;
end if; 
case c is
when @'#' => if (loc>1) and then (buffer(loc-2) in @'0'..@'9') then
	       scanning_based_number:=TRUE;
             end if; return @'#';
when @'A'..@'Z' ! @'a'..@'z' => @+@<Get an identifier@>;
when @'@@'=> @+@<Get control code and possible module name@>;
@/@t\4@>@<Compress two-symbol combinations like `\.{:=}'@>@;
when @' ' ! tab_mark => @+goto restart; {ignore spaces and tabs}
when @'{' => @+skip_comment; goto restart;
when @''' => @+@<If this is the beginning of an character token then set
	       |scanning_character| to |TRUE| and
	       |return character_tok|; otherwise do nothing@>;
when others => @+null;
end case;
return c;
end get_next;
 
@ 
@d compress(#)==if loc<=limit then c:=#; incr(loc); end if@;
 
@<Compress two-symbol...@>=
when @'.' => if buffer(loc)=@'.' then compress(double_dot); end if;
when @':' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(left_arrow); end if;
when @'=' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(equivalence_sign);
	     elsif buffer(loc)=@'>' then compress(right_arrow);
	     end if;
when @'>' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(greater_or_equal);
	     elsif buffer(loc)=@'>' then compress(right_label_bracket);
	     end if;
when @'<' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(less_or_equal);
	     elsif buffer(loc)=@'<' then compress(left_label_bracket);
	     elsif buffer(loc)=@'>' then compress(box_sign);
	     end if;
when @'/' => if buffer(loc)=@'=' then compress(not_equal); end if;
when @'*' => if buffer(loc)=@'*' then compress(double_star); end if;
 
@ We have to look at the preceding character to make sure this isn't part
of a real constant, before trying to find an identifier starting with
`\.e' or `\.E'.
 
@<Get an identifier@>=
if (((c=@'e')or(c=@'E'))and(loc>1)) and then
  ((buffer(loc-2) in @'0'..@'9') or buffer(loc-2)=@'#') then c:=0;
end if;
if c/=0 then
  decr(loc); id_first:=loc;
  repeat incr(loc); d:=buffer(loc);
  until(((d<@'0')or((d>@'9')and(d<@'A'))or((d>@'Z')and(d<@'a'))or
	     (d>@'z')) and (d/=@'_'));
  if loc>id_first+1 then
    id_loc:=loc;
    return identifier;
  end if; 
else return @'E'; {exponent of a real constant}
end if@;
 
@ After an \.{@@} sign has been scanned, the next character tells us
whether there is more work to do.
 
@<Get control code and possible module name@>=
c:=control_code(buffer(loc)); incr(loc);
if c=ignore then goto restart;
elsif c=module_name then
  @<Scan the module name and make |cur_module| point to it@>;
elsif c=control_text then
  repeat c:=skip_ahead;
  until(c/=@'@@');
  if buffer(loc-1)/=@'>' then
    err_print("! Improper @@ within control text");
@.Improper \AT! within control text@>
  end if;
  goto restart;
elsif c=ascii_tok then
  if (buffer(loc+1)=@''') or else
     (buffer(loc..loc+2)=(@'@@',@'@@',@''')) then
    scanning_character:=TRUE;
  else err_print("! Improper ASCII-code sequence, ' sign mising");
@.Improper ASCII-code sequence...@>
  end if;
end if@;
 
@ @<Scan the module name...@>=
@<Put module name into |mod_text(1..k)|@>;
if (k>3) and then (mod_text(k-2..k)=(@'.',@'.',@'.')) then
  cur_module:=prefix_lookup(k-3);
else cur_module:=mod_lookup(k);
end if@;
 
@ Module names are placed into the |mod_text| array with consecutive spaces,
tabs, and carriage-returns replaced by single spaces. There will be no
spaces at the beginning or the end. (We set |mod_text(0):=@' '| to facilitate
this, since the |mod_lookup| routine uses |mod_text(1)| as the first
character of the name.)
 
@<Set init...@>=mod_text(0):=@' ';
 
@ @<Put module name...@>=
k:=0;
loop  if loc>limit then
    get_line;
    if input_has_ended then
      err_print("! Input ended in section name"); @/
@.Input ended in section name@>
      exit;
    end if;
  end if;
  d:=buffer(loc);
  @<If end of name, |exit@;|@>;
  incr(loc); if k<longest_name-1 then incr(k); end if;
  if (d=@' ')or(d=tab_mark) then
    d:=@' '; if mod_text(k-1)=@' ' then decr(k); end if;
  end if;
  mod_text(k):=d;
end loop;
@<Check for overlong name@>;
if (mod_text(k)=@' ')and(k>0) then decr(k); end if@;
 
@ @<If end of name,...@>=
if d=@'@@' then
  d:=buffer(loc+1);
  if d=@'>' then
    loc:=loc+2; exit;
  elsif (d=@' ')or(d=tab_mark)or(d=@'*') then
    err_print("! Section name didn't end"); @/ exit;
@.Section name didn't end@>
  end if;
  incr(k); mod_text(k):=@'@@'; incr(loc); {now |d=buffer(loc)| again}
end if@;
 
@ @<Check for overlong name@>=
if k>=longest_name-2 then
  print_nl("! Section name too long: ");
@.Section name too long@>
  for j in INTEGER range 1..25 loop print(xchr(mod_text(j))); end loop;
  print("..."); mark_harmless;
end if@;
 
@ @<If this is the beginning...@>=
if (buffer(loc+1)=@''') or else
    (buffer(loc..loc+2)=(@'@@',@'@@',@''')) then
  scanning_character:=TRUE;
  return character_tok;
end if@;

@* Scanning a macro definition.
The rules for generating the replacement texts corresponding to simple
macros, parametric macros, and \ADA\ texts of a module are almost
identical, so a single procedure is used for all three cases. The
differences are that
 
\yskip\item{a)} The sign |#| denotes a parameter only when it appears
outside of strings in a parametric macro; otherwise it stands for the
ASCII character |#|. 
 
\item{b)}Module names are not allowed in simple macros or parametric macros;
in fact, the appearance of a module name terminates such macros and denotes
the name of the current module.
 
\item{c)}The symbols \.{@@d} and \.{@@f} and \.{@@a} are not allowed after
module names, while they terminate macro definitions.
 
@ Therefore there is a procedure |scan_repl| whose parameter |t| specifies
either |simple| or |parametric| or |module_name|. After |scan_repl| has
acted, |cur_repl_text| will point to the replacement text just generated, and
|next_control| will contain the control code that terminated the activity.

@<Types...@>=
@!cur_repl_text:text_pointer; {replacement text formed by |scan_repl|}
@!next_control:sixteen_bits;
 
@ @<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!scan_repl(@!t:eight_bits)is {creates a replacement text}
@!a:sixteen_bits; {the current token}
@!b:ASCII_code; {a character from the buffer}
@!bal:eight_bits:=0; {left parentheses minus right parentheses}
begin 
loop  <<continue>> a:=get_next;
  case a is
  when @'(' => @+incr(bal);
  when @')' => @+if bal=0 then @+err_print("! Extra )");
@.Extra )@>
    @+else@+ decr(bal);
    end if;
  when @'"' => @+@<Copy a string from the buffer to |tok_mem|@>;
  when character_tok ! ascii_tok => @+app_repl(a); a:=get_next;
  when @'#' => @+if t=parametric then @+ a:=param; end if; @/
  @t\4@>@<In cases that |a| is a non-ASCII token (|identifier|,
  |module_name|, etc.), either process it and change |a| to a byte
  that should be stored, or |goto continue| if |a| should be ignored,
  or |exit when a| signals the end of this replacement text@>@;
  when others => @+null;
  end case;
  app_repl(a); {store |a| in |tok_mem|}
  end loop;
next_control:=a;@/
@<Make sure the parentheses balance@>;
if text_ptr>max_texts-zz then overflow("text");end if;
cur_repl_text:=text_ptr; tok_start(text_ptr+zz):=tok_ptr(z);
incr(text_ptr);
if z=zz-1 then z:=0; else incr(z); end if;
end scan_repl;
 
@ @<Make sure the parentheses balance@>=
if bal>0 then
  if bal=1 then err_print("! Missing )");
  else new_ln; print("! Missing "); print_int(bal,1); print(" )'s"); error;
  end if;
@.Missing n )@>
  while bal>0 loop
    app_repl(@')'); decr(bal);
    end loop;
end if@;
 
@ @<In cases that |a| is...@>=
when identifier => @+a:=id_lookup(normal); app_repl((a/8#400#)+8#200#);
  a:=a mod 8#400#;
when module_name => exit when t/=module_name;@/
    app_repl((cur_module/8#400#)+8#250#);
    a:=cur_module mod 8#400#;
when verbatim => @+@<Copy verbatim string from the buffer to |tok_mem|@>;
when output_tok => @+@<Copy output file-name from the buffer to |tok_mem|@>;
when definition ! format ! begin_ada => exit when t/=module_name;@/
  err_print("! @@"&xchr(buffer(loc-1))&
@.\AT!a is ignored in ADA text@>
@.\AT!d is ignored in ADA text@>
@.\AT!f is ignored in ADA text@>
      " is ignored in ADA text"); @/ goto continue;
when new_module => @+exit;
 
@ @<Copy a string...@>=
b:=@'"';
loop  
  app_repl(b);
  if b=@'@@' then 
    if buffer(loc)=@'@@' then incr(loc); {store only one \.{@@}}
    else err_print("! You should double @@ signs in strings");
@.You should double \AT! signs@>
    end if;
  end if;
  if loc=limit then
    err_print("! String didn't end"); @/
@.String didn't end@>
    buffer(loc..loc+1):=(@'"',0);
  end if;
  b:=buffer(loc); incr(loc);
  if b=@'"' then
    exit when buffer(loc)/=@'"';@/
    incr(loc); app_repl(@'"');
  end if;
end loop@; {now |a| holds the final |@'"'| that will be stored}
 
@ @<Copy verbatim string...@>=
app_repl(verbatim);
buffer(limit+1):=@'@@';
while buffer(loc)/=@'@@' loop
  app_repl(buffer(loc));
  incr(loc);
  if (loc<limit) and then (buffer(loc..loc+1)=(@'@@',@'@@')) then
      app_repl(@'@@');
      loc:=loc+2;
  end if;
end loop;
if loc>=limit then err_print("! Verbatim string didn't end");
  if loc>=buf_size-1 then loc:=buf_size-2; end if;
@.Verbatim string didn't end@>
elsif buffer(loc+1)/=@'>' then 
  err_print("! You should double @@ signs in verbatim strings");
@.You should double \AT! signs@>
end if;
loc:=loc+2@; {another |verbatim| byte will be stored, since |a=verbatim|}
 
@ @<Copy output file-name...@>=
app_repl(output_tok);
buffer(limit+1):=@'@@';
while buffer(loc)/=@'@@' loop
  app_repl(buffer(loc));
  incr(loc);
  if (loc<limit) and then (buffer(loc..loc+1)=(@'@@',@'@@')) then
      app_repl(@'@@');
      loc:=loc+2;
  end if;
end loop;
if loc>=limit then err_print("! Output file name didn't end");
@.Output file name didn't end@>
elsif buffer(loc+1)/=@'>' then 
  err_print("! You should double @@ signs in output file-names");
@.You should double \AT! signs@>
end if;
loc:=loc+2@; {another |output_tok| byte will be stored, since |a=output_tok|}
 
@ The following procedure is used to define a simple or parametric macro,
just after the `\.{==}' of its definition has been scanned.
 
@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!define_macro(@!t:eight_bits)is
@!p:name_pointer; {the identifier being defined}
begin p:=id_lookup(t); scan_repl(t);@/
equiv(p):=cur_repl_text; text_link(cur_repl_text):=0;
end define_macro;
 
@* Scanning a module.
The |scan_module| procedure starts when `\.{@@\ }' or `\.{@@*}' has been
sensed in the input, and it proceeds until the end of that module.  It
uses |module_count| to keep track of the current module number; with luck,
\.{AWEAVE} and \.{ATANGLE} will both assign the same numbers to modules.
 
@<Types...@>=
@!module_count:mod_range; {the current module number}
 
@ The top level of |scan_module| is trivial.

@<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!scan_module is
@!p:name_pointer; {module name for the current module}
begin incr(module_count);@/
@<Scan the definition part of the current module@>;@/
@<Scan the \ADA\ part of the current module@>;
end scan_module;
 
@ @<Scan the definition part...@>=
next_control:=0;
loop <<continue>> while next_control<=format loop
    next_control:=skip_ahead;
    if next_control=module_name then
      {we want to scan the module name too}
      loc:=loc-2; next_control:=get_next;
    end if;
  end loop;
  exit when next_control/=definition;@/
  next_control:=get_next; {get identifier name}
  if next_control/=identifier then
    err_print("! Definition flushed, must start with "&
@.Definition flushed...@>
      "identifier of length > 1"); @/ goto continue;
  end if;
  next_control:=get_next; {get token after the identifier}
  if next_control=equivalence_sign then
    define_macro(simple); goto continue;
  else @<If the next text is `|(#)==|', call |define_macro|
    and |goto continue|@>;
  end if;
  err_print("! Definition flushed since it starts badly");
@.Definition flushed...@>
end loop@;
 
@ @<If the next text is `|(#)==|'...@>=
if next_control=@'(' then
  next_control:=get_next;
  if next_control=@'#' then
    next_control:=get_next;
    if next_control=@')' then
      next_control:=get_next;
      if next_control=@'=' then
	err_print("! Use == for macros"); @/
@.Use == for macros@>
        next_control:=equivalence_sign;
      end if;
      if next_control=equivalence_sign then
        define_macro(parametric); goto continue;
      end if;
    end if;
  end if;
end if@;
 
@ @<Scan the \ADA...@>=
case next_control is
when begin_ada => p:=0;
when module_name => p:=cur_module;@/
  @<Check that |=| or |==| follows this module name, otherwise |return@;|@>;
when others => return;
end case;
@<Insert the module number into |tok_mem|@>;
scan_repl(module_name); {now |cur_repl_text| points to the replacement text}
@<Update the data structure so that the replacement text is accessible@>@;
 
@ @<Check that |=|...@>=
repeat next_control:=get_next;
until(next_control/=@'+'); {allow optional `\.{+=}'}
if (next_control/=@'=')and(next_control/=equivalence_sign) then
  err_print("! ADA text flushed, = sign is missing");
@.ADA text flushed...@>
  repeat next_control:=skip_ahead;
  until(next_control=new_module);
  return;
end if@;
 
@ @<Insert the module number...@>=
store_two_bytes(8#150000#+module_count)@; {|8#150000#=8#320#*8#400#|}
 
@ @<Update the data...@>=
if p=0 then {unnamed module}
  text_link(last_unnamed):=cur_repl_text; last_unnamed:=cur_repl_text;
elsif equiv(p)=0 then equiv(p):=cur_repl_text; {first module of this name}
else  p:=equiv(p);
  while text_link(p)<module_flag loop p:=text_link(p); {find end of list}
  end loop;
  text_link(p):=cur_repl_text;
end if;
text_link(cur_repl_text):=module_flag@;
  {mark this replacement text as a nonmacro}

@ @<Procedures in |input_phase|@>=
procedure @!phase_i is
begin
@<Initialize the input system@>;
print_ln(banner); {print a ``banner line''}
@<Phase I: Read all the user's text and compress it into |tok_mem|@>;
end phase_i;

@* The main program.
We have defined plenty of procedures, and it is time to put the last
pieces of the puzzle in place. Here is where \.{ATANGLE} starts, and where
it ends.
@^system dependencies@>

@d web_input_file_name=="input.aweb"
@d change_input_file_name=="input.ach"
@d ada_output_file_name=="web_output.a"
@<Types...@>=
@!opened:BOOLEAN:=FALSE; {was previous |open_a_file| succesfull?}

@
@a@~tangle.a@>
with Ada.Command_Line; use Ada.Command_Line;
with TEXT_IO,int_number_io;
with data_structures,input_output,input_phase,output_phase;
use  data_structures,input_output,input_phase,output_phase;
procedure @!ATANGLE is
 ac : INTEGER := 0;
 begin
  print_ln("Trying to open input file.");
  ac := Argument_Count;
  if ac < 1 then
    fatal_error("No file on command line");
  end if;
  open_a_file(web_file,TEXT_IO.IN_FILE,Argument(1),opened);
  if not opened then
    fatal_error("AWEB file not open");
@.AWEB file not open@>
  end if;
  opened := FALSE;
  if ac >=2 then
    open_a_file(change_file,TEXT_IO.IN_FILE,Argument(2),opened);
  end if;
  if not opened then
    new_ln; print_ln("! No change file.");
@.No change file.@>
  end if;
  open_a_file(ada_file,TEXT_IO.OUT_FILE,ada_output_file_name,opened);
  if (not opened) and then
     (not create_ada_file(ada_output_file_name)) then
    fatal_error("ADA file not open");
@.ADA file not open@>
  end if;
  fn_length:=TEXT_IO.NAME(ada_file)'LAST;
  file_name(1..fn_length):=TEXT_IO.NAME(ada_file);
  f_line:=1;
  phase_i;
stat for zo in z_range loop max_tok_ptr(zo):=tok_ptr(zo); end loop; tats@;@/
  phase_ii;
raise end_of_ATANGLE;
exception
when @!@!end_of_ATANGLE =>
stat @<Print statistics about memory usage@>; tats@;@/
@t\4\4@>@;{here files should be closed if the operating system requires it}
@<Print the job |history|@>;
end ATANGLE;
 
@ @<Phase I:...@>=
phase_one:=TRUE;
module_count:=0;
repeat next_control:=skip_ahead;
until(next_control=new_module);
while not input_has_ended loop scan_module; end loop;
@<Check that all changes have been read@>;
phase_one:=FALSE@;
 
@ @<Print statistics about memory usage@>=
print_nl("Memory usage statistics:"); new_ln;
print_int(name_ptr,1); print(" names, "); print_int(text_ptr,1);
print_ln(" replacement texts;");
print_int(byte_ptr(0),1);
for wo in 1..ww-1 loop print("+"); print_int(byte_ptr(wo),1);
end loop;
print(" bytes, "); print_int(max_tok_ptr(0),1);
for zo in 1..zz-1 loop print("+"); print_int(max_tok_ptr(zo),1);
end loop;
print(" tokens.")@;
 
@ Some implementations may wish to pass the |history| value to the
operating system so that it can be used to govern whether or not other
programs are started. Here we simply report the history to the user.
@^system dependencies@>
 
@<Print the job |history|@>=
case history is
when spotless => @+print_nl("(No errors were found.)");
when harmless_message => @+print_nl("(Did you see the warning message above?)");
when error_message => @+print_nl("(Pardon me, but I think I spotted something wrong.)");
when fatal_message => @+print_nl("(That was a fatal error, my friend.)");
end case; {there are no other cases}
new_ln@;
 
@* System-dependent changes.
This module should be replaced, if necessary, by changes to the program
that are necessary to make \.{ATANGLE} work at a particular installation.
It is usually best to design your change file so that all changes to
previous modules preserve the module numbering; then everybody's version
will be consistent with the printed program. More extensive changes,
which introduce new modules, can be inserted here; then only the index
itself will get a new module number.
@^system dependencies@>
 
@* Index.
Here is a cross-reference table for the \.{ATANGLE} processor.
All modules in which an identifier is
used are listed with that identifier, except that reserved words are
indexed only when they appear in format definitions, and the appearances
of identifiers in module names are not indexed.
Underlined entries of subprograms and packages correspond to sections where
this entity is specified, whereas entries in italic type correspond to
the section where the entity's body is stated.
For any other identifier underlined entries correspond to where the
identifier was declared. Error messages and
a few other things like ``ASCII code'' are indexed here too.
 
 
 
 
